\id 1KI Original Douay-Rheims Bible
\ide UTF-8
\h 3 Kings
\mt1 The Third Book of Kings, according to the Hebrews the First of Malachim. מלכים
\c 1
\p
\v 1 And king David was old, and had many days of age: & when he was covered with cloths, he was not warmed. \f + \fr 1:1 \ft The first part. King David's admonitions to his son: and his death.\f*
\v 2 His servants therefore said to him: Let us seek for our lord the king a young woman a virgin, and let her stand before the king, and cherish him, and sleep in his bosom, and warm our lord the king.
\v 3 They sought therefore a beautiful young woman in all the coasts of Israel, and they found Abisag a Sunamite, & brought her to the king.
\v 4 And the damsel was exceeding beautiful, and she slept with the king, and served him, but the king did not know her.
\v 5 And Adonias the son of Haggith was elevated, saying: I will reign. And he made himself chariots & horsemen, & fifty men, that should run before him.
\v 6 Neither did his father control him at any time, saying: Why didst thou this? And he also was very beautiful, the second born after Absalom.
\v 7 And he had talk with Joab the son of Sarvia, and with Abiathar the priest, who furthered Adonias' side. \f + \fr 1:7 \ft For this conspiracy Abiathar was deposed. ch. 2. v. 27.\f*
\v 8 But Sadoc the Priest, and Banaias the son of Joiada, and Nathan the Prophet, and Semei, and Rei, and the strength of David's army was not with Adonias.
\v 9 Adonias therefore having immolated rams and calves, and all fat beasts beside the Stone zoheleth, which was nigh to the Fountain Rogel, called all his brethren the sons of the king, and all the men of Juda the servants of the king:
\v 10 But Nathan the Prophet, and Banaias, and all the strong ones, and Salomon his brother he called not.
\v 11 Nathan therefore said to Bethsabee the mother of Salomon: Hast thou not heard that Adonias the son of Haggith hath reigned, & our lord David is ignorant thereof?
\v 12 Now therefore come, take counsel of me, & save thy life, & thy son Salomon's.
\v 13 Go, & enter in to king David, & say to him: Didst not thou my lord king swear to me thy handmaid, saying: Salomon thy son shall reign after me, and he shall sit in my throne? Why then reigneth Adonias?
\v 14 And whiles thou art yet speaking there with the king, I will come after thee, & make up thy words.
\v 15 Bethsabee therefore went in to the king in the chamber: and the king was exceeding old, and Abisag the Sunamite ministered to him.
\v 16 Bethsabee bowed herself, and adored the king. To whom the king said: What is thy will? Quoth he.
\v 17 Who answering said: My lord, thou didst swear to thy handmaid by our Lord thy God, that Salomon thy son shall reign after me, and he shall sit in my throne.
\v 18 And behold now Adonias reigneth, thou my lord the king not knowing thereof.
\v 19 He hath killed oxen, and all fat things, and many rams, and called all the king's sons. Abiathar also the Priest, and Joab the General of the warfare: but Salomon thy servant he called not.
\v 20 Notwithstanding my lord king, the eyes of all Israel look upon thee, that thou wouldest shew them, who shall sit in thy throne my lord king after thee.
\v 21 And it shall be when my lord king sleepeth with his fathers, I & my son Salomon shall be sinners. \f + \fr 1:21 \ft Basely esteemed, or punished as offenders upon suspicion or jealousy.\f*
\v 22 As she was yet speaking with the king, Nathan the Prophet came.
\v 23 And they told the king, saying: Nathan the Prophet is here. And when he was gone in to the king, and had adored bowing to the earth,
\v 24 Nathan said: My lord king, didst thou say: Let Adonias reign after me, and let him sit upon my throne?
\v 25 Because he is gone down today, and hath immolated oxen, and fatlings, and many rams, and called all the king's sons, and the captains of the army, Abiathar also the Priest: and they eating and drinking before him, and saying: God save the king Adonias:
\v 26 me thy servant, and Sadoc the Priest, and Banaias the son of Joiada, and Salomon thy servant he called not.
\v 27 Is this word proceeding from my lord the king, and hast thou not told me thy servant who should sit upon the throne of my lord the king after him?
\v 28 And king David answered, saying: Call unto me Bethsabee. Who when she was entered in to the king, and stood before him,
\v 29 the king sware, and said: Our Lord liveth, which hath delivered my soul from all distress,
\v 30 that as I sware to thee by our Lord the God of Israel, saying: Salomon thy son shall reign after me, and he shall sit upon my throne for me, so will I do this day.
\v 31 And Bethsabee bowing her countenance unto the earth adored the king, saying: God save my lord for ever.
\v 32 King David also said: Call me Sadoc the priest, and Nathan the prophet, & Banaias the son of Joiada. Who when they were entered in before the king,
\v 33 he said to them: Take with you the servants of your lord, and set Salomon my son upon my mule: and bring him into Gihon.
\v 34 And let Sadoc the priest anoint him there, and Nathan the prophet to be king over Israel: and you shall sound the trumpet, and shall say: God save king Salomon.
\v 35 And you shall go up after him, and he shall come, and shall sit upon my throne, and he shall reign for me: and I will ordain him that he be Prince over Israel, and over Juda.
\v 36 And Banaias the son of Joiada answered the king, saying: Amen: so speak our Lord the God of my lord the king.
\v 37 As our Lord hath been with my lord the king, so be he with Salomon, and make his throne higher than the throne of my lord king David.
\v 38 Sadoc therefore the Priest, and Nathan the Prophet went down, and Banaias the son of Joiada, and Cerethi, and Phelethi: and they set Salomon upon the mule of king David, and brought him into Gihon.
\v 39 And Sadoc the priest took a horn of oil out of the tabernacle, and anointed Salomon: and they sounded the trumpet, and all the people said: God save king Salomon.
\v 40 And all the multitude went up after him, and the people singing on shalms, and rejoicing with great gladness, and the earth sounded of their cry.
\v 41 And Adonias heard, and all that were invited of him, and the feast was ended: yea & Joab hearing the voice of the trumpet, said: What meaneth the cry of the city making a tumult?
\v 42 As he yet spake, came Jonathas the son of Abiathar the Priest: to whom Adonias said: Come in, because thou art a stout man, and bringest good news.
\v 43 And Jonathas answered Adonias: Not so: for our lord king David hath appointed Salomon king,
\v 44 and hath sent with him Sadoc the Priest, and Nathan the Prophet, and Banaias the son of Joiada, and Cerethi, and Phelethi, and they have set him upon the king's mule.
\v 45 And Sadoc the Priest, and Nathan the Prophet have anointed him king in Gihon: & they are gone up thence rejoicing, and the city sounded: this is the voice that you heard.
\v 46 Yea and Salomon sitteth upon the throne of the Kingdom.
\v 47 And the king's servants entering in, have blessed our lord king David, saying: God amplify the name of Salomon above thy name, and magnify his throne above thy throne. And the king adored in his bed: \f + \fr 1:47 \ft King David did not adore his son as a subject adoreth his Prince, but adored God, giving thanks for this benefit of a successor, as it followeth in the next verse.\f*
\v 48 and he hath thus spoken: Blessed be our Lord the God of Israel, who hath given this day one sitting in my throne, mine eyes seeing it.
\v 49 They therefore were terrified, and they all arose, that had been invited of Adonias, and every man went his way.
\v 50 And Adonias fearing Salomon arose, & went, & held the horn of the altar.
\v 51 And they told Salomon, saying: Behold Adonias fearing king Salomon, hath taken hold of the horn of the altar, saying: Let king Salomon swear to me this day, that he will not kill his servant with the sword.
\v 52 And Salomon said: If he be a good man, there shall not so much as one hair of his fall upon the ground: but if evil shall be found in him, he shall die.
\v 53 King Salomon therefore sent, and brought him out from the altar: and going in he adored king Salomon: and Salomon said to him: Go to thy house.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 And the days of David approached that he should die, and he commanded his son Salomon, saying:
\v 2 I enter into the way of all flesh: take courage, and play the man.
\v 3 And observe the watches of our Lord thy God, that thou walk in his ways, and keep his ceremonies, and his precepts & judgments, and testimonies as is written in the law of Moyses: that thou mayst understand all things which thou doest, and whithersoever thou shalt turn thyself:
\v 4 that our Lord may confirm his words, which he hath spoken of me, saying: If thy children shall keep their ways, and shall walk before me in truth, in all their heart, and in all their soul, there shall not altogether be taken from thee a man out of the throne of Israel.
\v 5 Thou knowest also what Joab the son of Sarvia hath done to me, what he did to the two Princes of the army of Israel, to Abner the son of Ner, & Amasa the son of Jether: whom he slew, & shed the blood of war in peace, and put the blood of battle in his belt, which was about his loins, and in his shoe, which was on his feet.
\v 6 Thou shalt do therefore according to thy wisdom, and shalt not bring his hoar head peaceably unto hell.
\v 7 But to the sons also of Berzellai the Galaadite thou shalt render kindness, and they shall eat on thy table: for they met me when I fled from the face of Absalom thy brother.
\v 8 Thou shalt also with thee Semei the son of Gera the son of Jemini of Bahurim, who cursed me with a wicked curse, when I went to the Camp; but because he came down to meet me when I passed Jordan, and I sware to him by our Lord, saying: I will not kill thee with the sword;
\v 9 do not thou suffer him to be guiltless. But thou art a wise man, so that thou knowest what thou shalt do to him, and thou shalt bring his hoar hair with blood unto hell.
\v 10 David therefore slept with his fathers, & was buried in the city of David.
\v 11 And the days that David reigned in Israel, are forty years: in Hebron he reigned seven years, in Jerusalem thirty three.
\v 12 And Salomon sat upon the throne of David his father, & his Kingdom was confirmed exceedingly. \f + \fr 2:12 \ft The second part. Of Salomon's reign, and acts good and bad.\f*
\v 13 And Adonias the son of Haggith entered in to Bethsabee the mother of Salomon. Who said to him: Is thy coming peaceable? Who answered: Peaceable.
\v 14 And he added: I have a word to speak with thee. To whom she said: Speak. And he:
\v 15 Thou knowest, quoth he, that the kingdom was mine, & all Israel had purposed to make me over them to be their king: but the kingdom is transposed, & is made my brother's: for it was appointed him of our Lord.
\v 16 Now therefore I desire one petition of thee; Confound not my face. Who said to him: Speak.
\v 17 And he said: I pray speak to Salomon the king (for he cannot deny thee any thing) that he give me Abisag the Sunamite to wife.
\v 18 And Bethsabee said: Well, I will speak for thee to the king.
\v 19 Bethsabee therefore came to king Salomon, to speak unto him for Adonias: & the king arose to meet her, & adored her, & sat down upon his throne: & a throne was set for the king's mother, who sat on his right hand.
\v 20 And she said to him: One little petition I desire of thee, confound not my face. And the king said to her: My mother ask: for it behoveth not that I turn away thy face. \f + \fr 2:20 \ft In all convenient suits it behoveth the son to hear his mother.\f*
\v 21 Who said: Let Abisag the Sunamite be given to Adonias thy brother to wife.
\v 22 And king Salomon answered, and said to his mother: Why doest thou ask Abisag the Sunamite for Adonias? Ask for him also the Kingdom: for he is my brother elder than I, & hath Abiathar the priest, & Joab the son of Sarvia.
\v 23 Therefore king Salomon sware by our Lord, saying: These things do God to me, & these add he, because Adonias hath spoken this word against his life.
\v 24 And now, our Lord liveth which hath established me, & placed me upon the throne of David my father, and which hath made me a house, as he spake, this day shall Adonias be slain.
\v 25 And king Salomon sent by the hand of Banaias the son of Joiada, who slew him, & he died.
\v 26 To Abiathar also the priest the king said: Go into Anathoth to thy field, and thou indeed art a man of death: but today I will not kill thee, because thou didst carry the ark of our Lord God before David my father, & hast sustained labour in all things, wherein my father laboured.
\v 27 Salomon therefore cast out Abiathar, that he should not be the priest of our Lord, that the word of our Lord might be fulfilled, which he spake concerning the house of Heli in Silo. \f + \fr 2:27 \ft By special instinct Salomon did this extraordinary fact as a Prophet & minister of God, executing his sentence given before against the house of Heli for the sins of his children, 1. Reg. 2. v. 11. and for Abiathar's proper fault joining with Adonias against Salomon. 3. Reg. 1.\f*
\v 28 And then a messenger came to Joab, for that Joab had turned after Adonias, and after Salomon had not turned: Joab therefore fled into the tabernacle of our Lord, & caught the horn of the altar.
\v 29 And it was told king Salomon, that Joab was fled into the tabernacle of our Lord, and was beside the altar: and Salomon sent Banaias the son of Joiada, saying: Go, kill him
\v 30 And Banaias came to the tabernacle of our Lord, and said to him: Thus saith the king: Come forth. Who said: I will not come forth, but here will I die. Banaias reported his word to the king, saying: Thus spake Joab, and thus he answered me.
\v 31 And the king said to him: Do as he hath spoken: and kill him, and bury him, and thou shalt remove the innocent blood, which hath been shed of Joab, from me, and from the house of my father.
\v 32 And our Lord shall render his blood upon his head, because he murdered two just men, and better than himself: and slew them with his sword, my father David not knowing, Abner the son of Ner general of the warfare of Israel, and Amasa the son of Jether general of the army of Juda:
\v 33 and their blood shall return upon the head of Joab, and upon the head of his seed for ever. But to David & his seed & his house, & to his throne be peace for ever from our Lord.
\v 34 Banaias therefore the son of Joiada went up, and setting upon him slew him: and he was buried in his house in the desert.
\v 35 And the king appointed Banaias the son of Joiada for him over the army, and Sadoc the priest he placed for Abiathar. \f + \fr 2:35 \ft Salomon was not only a King but also a Prophet. Moreover some secular Princes do nominate superiors, and install them in their seats, yet their jurisdiction is not depending on the Prince, but the Prince to be directed by them. Num. 27. v. 21.\f*
\v 36 The king also sent, and called Semei, and said to him: Build thee a house in Jerusalem, and dwell there: and thou shalt not go out thence hither and thither.
\v 37 But what day soever thou shalt go out, and shalt pass the Torrent Cedron, know that thou art to be slain: thy blood shall be upon thy head.
\v 38 And Semei said to the king: The saying is good: as my lord the king hath spoken, so will thy servant do. Semei therefore dwelt in Jerusalem many days.
\v 39 And it came to pass after three years, that the servants of Semei fled to Achis the son of Maacha the king of Geth: and it was told Semei that his servants were gone into Geth.
\v 40 And Semei arose, and saddled his ass, & went to Achis into Geth to require his servants, & he brought them out of Geth.
\v 41 And it was told Salomon that Semei went into Geth out of Jerusalem, & was returned.
\v 42 And sending he called him, & said to him: Did I not testify to thee by our Lord, & told thee before: What day soever thou going out shalt pass hither and thither, know that thou shalt die? And thou didst answer me: The saying is good, which I have heard.
\v 43 Why then hast thou not kept the oath of our Lord, and the precept that I commanded thee?
\v 44 And the king said to Semei: Thou knowest all the evil, whereof thy heart is privy to thyself, which thou didst to David my father: our Lord hath rendered thy malice upon thy head.
\v 45 And king Salomon be blessed, and the throne of David shall be stable before our Lord for ever.
\v 46 The king therefore commanded Banaias the son of Joiada: who going out, struck him, and he died.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 The kingdom therefore was established in the hand of Salomon, and he was joined in affinity to Pharao the king of Ægypt: for he took his daughter, and brought her into the city of David, until he accomplished building his own house, and the house of our Lord, and the wall of Jerusalem round about.
\v 2 But yet the people immolated in the excelses: for there was no temple built to the name of our Lord until that day.
\v 3 And Salomon loved our Lord, walking in the precepts of David his father, saving that he immolated in the excelses, and burnt incense.
\v 4 He went therefore into Gabaon, to immolate there: for that was a very great excelse: a thousand hosts for holocaust did Salomon offer upon that altar in Gabaon.
\v 5 And our Lord appeared to Salomon in a dream by night, saying: Ask what thou wilt that I may give it thee.
\v 6 And Salomon said: Thou hast done great mercy with thy servant David my father, even as he walked in thy sight in truth, and justice, and a right heart with thee: for thou hast kept thy great mercy, and hast given him a son sitting upon his throne, as it is this day.
\v 7 And now Lord God, thou hast made thy servant to reign for David my father, but I am a little child, and ignorant of my going out and coming in.
\v 8 And thy servant is in the midst of the people, which thou hast chosen, a people infinite, which cannot be numbered and counted for the multitude.
\v 9 Thou shalt therefore give to thy servant a docible heart, that he may judge the people, and discern between good & evil. For who shall be able to judge this people, this thy people great in number?
\v 10 The word therefore was liked before our Lord, that Salomon had asked such a thing.
\v 11 And our Lord said to Salomon: Because thou hast asked this thing, and hast not desired for thyself many days, nor riches, nor the lives of thine enemies, but hast desired wisdom for thyself to discern judgment:
\v 12 behold I have done unto thee according to thy words, and have given thee a wise heart and intelligent, in so much that none before thee hath been like thee, nor shall arise after thee.
\v 13 Yea and these things, which thou didst not ask, I have given thee; to wit, riches, and glory, so that none hath been like thee among the kings all days heretofore.
\v 14 And if thou wilt walk in my ways, and keep my precepts, & my commandments, as thy father walked, I will make thy days long.
\v 15 Therefore Salomon awaked, and perceived that it was a dream: and when he was come to Jerusalem, he stood before the ark of covenant of our Lord, and offered holocausts, and made pacific victims, and a great feast to all his servants.
\v 16 Then came there two women harlots to the king, and stood before him: \f + \fr 3:16 \ft The Epistle on Monday in the 4. week of Lent.\f*
\v 17 of the which one said: I beseech thee, my lord, I and this woman dwelt in one house, and I was delivered of a child beside her in the chamber.
\v 18 And the third day, after that I was delivered, she also was delivered, and we were together, and no other person with us in the house, except we two.
\v 19 And this woman's child died in the night. For sleeping she oppressed him.
\v 20 And rising in the dead time of the night, she took my child from the side of me thy handmaid being asleep, and laid it in her bosom: and her child that was dead, she put in my bosom.
\v 21 And when I was risen in the morning to give my child milk, he appeared dead: whom more diligently beholding when it was clear day, I found that it was not mine which I bare.
\v 22 And the other woman answered: It is not so as thou sayst, but thy child is dead, and mine liveth. On the contrary part she said: Thou liest: for my child liveth, and thy child is dead. And in this manner they strove before the king.
\v 23 Then said the king: This woman saith: My child liveth, and thy child is dead. And this hath answered, No, but thy child is dead, and mine liveth.
\v 24 The king therefore said: Bring me a sword. And when they had brought a sword before the king,
\v 25 Divide, quoth he, the living child into two parts, and give the half part to one, and half to the other.
\v 26 But the woman, whose child was alive, said to the king (for her bowels were moved upon her child) I beseech thee my lord, give her the child alive, and kill it not. On the contrary part she said: be it neither mine, nor thine, but let it be divided. \f + \fr 3:26 \ft So heretics not being able to prove that their synagogue is the true & permanent Church, would destroy the Catholic and so have none at all.\f*
\v 27 The king answered, and said: Give unto this woman the infant alive, and let it not be killed, for this is the mother thereof.
\v 28 All Israel therefore heard the judgment that the king had judged, and they feared the king, seeing the wisdom of God to be in him to do judgment.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 And king Salomon was reigning over all Israel:
\v 2 and these were the princes which he had: Azarias the son of Sadoc the priest:
\v 3 Elihoreph, and Ahia the sons of Sisa Scribes: Josaphat the son of Ahilud, register:
\v 4 Banaias the son of Joiada, over the army: and Sadoc, and Abiathar priests.
\v 5 Azarias the son of Nathan, over them that assisted the king: Zabud the son of Nathan priest, the king's friend:
\v 6 and Ahizar governor of the house: and Adoniram the son of Abda over the tributes.
\v 7 And Salomon had twelve governors over all Israel, which served out victuals for the king and for his house: for every one ministered necessaries, each man his month in the year.
\v 8 And these are their names: Benhur in mount Ephraim.
\v 9 Bendecar, in Macces, and in Salebim, and in Bethsames, and in Elon, and in Bethhanan.
\v 10 Benhesed in Aruboth: his was Socho, and all the land Epher.
\v 11 Benabinadab, whose was all Nepha Dor, had Tapheth the daughter of Salomon to wife.
\v 12 Bana the son of Ahilud governed Thanach and Mageddo, and all Bethsan, which is beside Sarthana under Jezrahel, from Bethsan unto Abelmehula over against Jecmaan.
\v 13 Bengaber in Ramoth Galaad: had Avothjair the son of Manasses in Galaad, he was chief in all the country of Argob, which is in Basan, three score cities great and walled, which had brazen locks.
\v 14 Ahinadab the son of Addo was chief in Manaim.
\v 15 Achimaas in Nephthali: yea he also had Basemath the daughter of Salomon in marriage.
\v 16 Baana the son of Husi, in Aser, and in Baloth.
\v 17 Josaphat the son of Pharue, in Issachar.
\v 18 Semei the son of Ela, in Benjamin.
\v 19 Gaber the son of Uri, in the land of Galaad in the land of Sehon the king of the Ammorrheite, & of Og the king of Basan, over all things that were in that Land.
\v 20 Juda and Israel innumerable, as the sand of the sea in multitude: eating, and drinking, and rejoicing.
\v 21 And Salomon was in his dominion, having all the Kingdoms with him from the river of the land of the Philisthiims unto the border of Ægypt: of them that offered him presents, & served him all the days of his life.
\v 22 And the provision of Salomon was every day thirty measures of flour, & threescore measures of meal,
\v 23 ten fat oxen and twenty pasture-fed, & a hundred rams, beside the venison of harts, roes, and buffles, and fatted fowl.
\v 24 For he possessed all the country, which was beyond the river, from Thapsa unto Gaza, and all the kings of those countries: and he had peace on every side round about.
\v 25 And Juda and Israel dwelt without any fear, every one under his vine, and under his fig tree, from Dan unto Bersabee all the days of Salomon.
\v 26 And Salomon had forty thousand stalls of chariot-horses, and twelve thousand for the saddle.
\v 27 And the foresaid governors of the king fed them: yea and the necessaries of king Salomon's table they gave forth with great care in their time.
\v 28 Barley also and straw for the horses, and beasts, they brought to the place, where the king was, according as it was appointed them.
\v 29 God also gave wisdom to Salomon and prudence exceeding much, and latitude of heart as the sand that is in the sea shore.
\v 30 And the wisdom of Salomon passed the wisdom of all them in the east, and of the Ægyptians,
\v 31 and he was wiser than all men: wiser than Ethan the Ezralite, and Heman, and Chalcol, & Dorda the sons of Mahol, and he was renowned in all nations round about.
\v 32 Salomon also spake three thousand parables: and his songs were a thousand & five. \f + \fr 4:32 \ft These books are not extant.\f*
\v 33 And he disputed of trees from the cedar that is in Libanus, unto the hyssop which cometh out of the wall: & he discoursed of beasts, and fowls, and creeping worms, and fishes.
\v 34 And there came from all people to hear the wisdom of Salomon, and from all the kings of the earth, which heard his wisdom.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 Hiram also the king of Tyre sent his servants to Salomon: for he heard that they had anointed him king for his father: because Hiram had been David's friend at all time.
\v 2 And Salomon sent to Hiram, saying:
\v 3 Thou knowest the will of David my father, and that he could not build a house to the name of our Lord his God, because of wars imminent round about, until our Lord put them under the sole of his feet.
\v 4 But now our Lord my God hath given me rest round about: and there is no satan, nor ill rencounter.
\v 5 Wherefore I purpose to build a temple to the name of our Lord my God, as our Lord hath spoken to David my father, saying: Thy son, whom I will give for thee upon thy throne, he shall build a house to my name.
\v 6 Command therefore that thy servants cut me down cedars out of Libanus, and let my servants be with thy servants: and I will give thee the hire of thy servants whatsoever thou wilt ask, for thou knowest how there is not in my people a man that hath skill to hew wood as the Sidonians.
\v 7 When Hiram therefore had heard the words of Salomon, he rejoiced exceedingly, and said: Blessed be the Lord God this day, who hath given unto David a son most wise over this people so great in number.
\v 8 And Hiram sent to Salomon, saying: I have heard whatsoever thou hast willed me: I will do all thy will in cedar trees, and fir trees.
\v 9 My servants shall bring them down from Libanus to the sea: and I will put them in boats in the sea, unto the place which thou shalt signify to me; & will land them there, and thou shalt take them: and thou shalt allow me necessaries, that there be meat given for my house.
\v 10 Therefore Hiram gave Salomon cedar trees, and fir trees, according to all his will.
\v 11 And Salomon allowed Hiram twenty thousand cores of wheat, for provision for his house, and twenty cores of most pure oil: these things did Salomon give to Hiram every year.
\v 12 Our Lord also gave wisdom to Salomon, as he spake to him: & there was peace between Hiram & Salomon, and both made a league.
\v 13 And king Salomon chose workmen out of all Israel, and the taxed number was of thirty thousand men.
\v 14 And he sent them into Libanus, ten thousand every month by course, so that two months they were in their houses: and Adoniram was over this taxing.
\v 15 And Salomon had seventy thousand of them that carried burdens, and eighty thousand hewers of stones in the mountain:
\v 16 besides the overseers which were over every work, in number three thousand, and three hundred that commanded the people, & them that did the work.
\v 17 And the king commanded, that they should take great stones, chosen stones for the foundation of the temple, and should square them:
\v 18 which the masons of Salomon, and masons of Hiram hewed: moreover the Giblians prepared timber and stones, to build the house.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 And it came to pass in the four hundred and four score year of the coming forth of the children of Israel out of the Land of Ægypt, in the fourth year, the month Zio (that is the second month) of the reign of Salomon over Israel, he began to build a house to our Lord.
\v 2 And the house, which king Salomon built to our Lord, had three score cubits in length, & twenty cubits in breadth, and thirty cubits in height.
\v 3 And there was a porch before the temple of twenty cubits of length, according to the measure of the breadth of the temple: and it had ten cubits of breadth before the face of the temple.
\v 4 And he made in the temple oblique windows. \f + \fr 6:4 \ft Narrow without & broad within.\f*
\v 5 And he built upon the wall of the temple lofts round about, in the walls of the house round about the temple and the oracle, and he made sides round about.
\v 6 The loft that was underneath, had five cubits of breadth, & the middle loft was of six cubits in breadth, and the third loft had seven cubits of breadth. And he put beams in the house round about on the outside, that they might not cleave to the walls of the temple.
\v 7 And the house when it was built, was built of stones hewed and perfected: and hammer, and hatchet, and all the tool of iron were not heard in the house when it was built. \f + \fr 6:7 \ft In perfect people is neither noise of murmur in adversity, nor of boasting in prosperity, but patience and humility with silence.\f*
\v 8 The door of the middle side was in the wall of the house on the right hand: and by winding stairs they went up into the middle room, and from the middle into the third.
\v 9 And he built the house, and finished it: he covered also the house with ceilings of cedar trees.
\v 10 And he built a loft over all the house five cubits of height, and he covered the house with cedar timber.
\v 11 And the word of our Lord came to Salomon, saying:
\v 12 This house, which thou buildest, if thou wilt walk in my precepts, and to my judgments, and keep all my commandments, going in them, I will establish my word to thee, which I spake to David thy father.
\v 13 And I will dwell in the midst of the children of Israel, and will not forsake my people Israel.
\v 14 Salomon therefore built the house, and finished it.
\v 15 And he built the walls of the house on the inside, with cedar lofts, from the pavement of the house to the top of the walls, and to the roofs, he covered it with cedar trees on the inside: and he covered the floor of the house with boards of fir.
\v 16 And he built lofts of cedar timber of twenty cubits at the hinder part of the temple, from the pavement to the higher parts: and he made the inner house of the oracle to be Sanctum Sanctorum. \f + \fr 6:16 \ft Holy of holies or most holy place.\f*
\v 17 Moreover the temple itself was forty cubits before the doors of the oracle.
\v 18 And all the house was covered within with cedar, having roundels, and the joints thereof cunningly wrought, and the engravings standing out: all things were covered with boards: neither could there a stone appear in the wall at all. \f + \fr 6:18 \ft Stones in buildings, and bones in living bodies represent the state of religious persons: who being hid in their Monasteries and cells, so much the more fortify the Church, by how much less they appear abroad, because their office is not to teach, but to mourn. S. Bernard. Ser. 64.\f*
\v 19 And he made the oracle in the midst of the house, in the inner part, that he might put the ark of covenant of our Lord there.
\v 20 Moreover the oracle had twenty cubits in length, and twenty cubits of breadth, and twenty cubits in height. And he covered and sealed it with most pure gold. And the altar also he decked with cedar.
\v 21 The house also before the oracle he covered with most pure gold, and fastened on plates with nails of gold.
\v 22 And there was nothing in the temple that was not covered with gold: yea and all the altar of the oracle he covered with gold.
\v 23 And he made in the oracle two Cherubs of olive trees, of ten cubits in height.
\v 24 One wing of a cherub of five cubits, and the other wing of a cherub five cubits: that is, having ten cubits, from the end of one wing unto the end of the other wing.
\v 25 Of ten cubits also was the second cherub: in like measure, and the work was one in both cherubs,
\v 26 that is to say, one cherub had the height of ten cubits, and in like manner the second cherub.
\v 27 And he put the cherubs in the midst of the inner temple: and the cherubs extended their wings, and the one wing touched the wall, and the wing of the second cherub touched the other wall: and the other wings in the middle part of the temple touched each other.
\v 28 He covered also the cherubs with gold.
\v 29 And all the walls of the temple round about he graved with diverse engravings and carving: & he made in them cherubs, and palm trees, and diverse pictures, as it were standing out of the wall, and coming forth. \f + \fr 6:29 \ft It is a clear case, that all carved and graven pictures, or images were not unlawful, but were religiously made & set in the holy Temple, for the more honour of God.\f*
\v 30 Yea the pavement also of the house he covered with gold within and without.
\v 31 And in the entrance of the oracle he made little doors of the timber of olivetrees, and five corner posts.
\v 32 And two doors of olivetimber: and he graved in them pictures of Cherubs, and figures of Palm trees, and graven works standing out very much; and he covered them with gold: and he covered as well the Cherubs and the palmtrees, and the other things with gold.
\v 33 And he made in the entrance of the temple posts of olivetimber four square:
\v 34 and two doors of fir trees, one against another: and either door was double, & so opened with folding leaves.
\v 35 And he graved Cherubs, and palmtrees, and engravings appearing very much: and he covered all with golden plates in square work by rule.
\v 36 And he built the inner court with three rows of stones polished, & one row of cedar timber.
\v 37 In the fourth year was the house of our Lord founded in the month of Zio:
\v 38 and in the eleventh year in the month Bul (that is the eighth month) the house was perfected in all the works thereof, and in all the implements thereof: and he was building it seven years. \f + \fr 6:38 \ft The end of the fourth age.\f*
\c 7
\p
\v 1 And his own house Salomon built in thirteen years, and brought it to perfection.
\v 2 He built also the house of the forest of Libanus of an hundred cubits in length, & fifty cubits in breadth, and thirty cubits in height: and four galleries between pillars of cedar: for he had cut cedar trees into pillars.
\v 3 And he decked the whole vault with boards of cedar, which was held up with five & forty pillars, And one order had fifteen pillars,
\v 4 set one against another,
\v 5 and looked one over against another, with equal space between the pillars, & over the pillars square beams in all equal.
\v 6 And the porch of the pillars he made of fifty cubits in length, and thirty cubits in breadth: and another porch before the greater porch: and pillars, and tops upon the pillars.
\v 7 He made also the porch of the throne, wherein the seat of judgment is; and covered it with cedar wood from the pavement unto the top.
\v 8 And the little house, where they sat in judgment, was in the midst of the porch of like work. He made also a house for the daughter of Pharao (which Salomon had taken to wife) of such work, as also this porch.
\v 9 All of chosen stones, which were sawed by a certain rule and measure both within and without: from the foundation to the top of the walls, and without unto the greater court.
\v 10 And the foundations of chosen stones, great stones of ten or eight cubits.
\v 11 And above there were hewed chosen stones of equal measure, and in like manner of cedar.
\v 12 And the greater court round with three rews of hewed stones, and one rew of planed cedar, moreover also in the inner court of the house of our Lord, and in the porch of the house.
\v 13 King Salomon also sent, and took Hiram from Tyre,
\v 14 the son of a widow woman of the tribe of Nephthali, his father, a Tyrian, an artificer in brass, and full of wisdom, and intelligence, and skill to make all work of brass. Who when he was come to king Salomon, made all his work.
\v 15 And he cast two brazen pillars, of eighteen cubits in height one pillar: and a line of twelve cubits compassed both pillars.
\v 16 He made also two little heads, which should be put upon the heads of the pillars, cast of brass: five cubits high one little head, and five cubits the other little head:
\v 17 and as it were in manner of a net, & of chains knit one to the other with marvelous work. Both little heads of the pillars were cast: seven rews of little nets in one little head, & seven little nets in the other little head.
\v 18 And finished the pillars, and two rews round about every net, that they might cover the little heads, which were over the top of the pomegranates: in like manner did he also to the second little head.
\v 19 And the little heads, that were upon the heads of the pillars, were made as it were with lily work, in the porch, of four cubits.
\v 20 And again other little heads in the top of the pillars above, according to the measure of the pillar against the little nets: and of the pomegranates were two hundred rews round about the second little head.
\v 21 And he set two pillars in the porch of the temple: & when he had erected the pillar on the right hand, he called the name thereof Iachin: in like manner he erected the second pillar, & called the name thereof Booz. \f + \fr 7:21 \ft * Firmness.\f* \f + \fr 7:21 \ft * in strength.\f*
\v 22 And upon the heads of the pillars he put a work in manner of a lily: and the work of the pillars was perfected.
\v 23 He made also a sea of founder's work, of ten cubits from brim to brim, round in compass, the height thereof was of five cubits, and a cord of thirty cubits did compass it round about. \f + \fr 7:23 \ft Avessel so called for the bigness being a great lavatory.\f*
\v 24 And the graving under the brim compassed it, ten cubits going about the lavatory: there were two rews of chamfered furrowed gravings cast.
\v 25 And it stood upon twelve oxen, of which three looked to the North, and three to the West, and three to the South, and three to the East, and the sea was over them: whose hinder parts were all hid inward.
\v 26 And the thickness of the lavatory was of three ounces: and the brim thereof as it were the brim of a chalice, and the leaf of crisped lily: it contained two thousand bates. \f + \fr 7:26 \ft Batus containeth about five gallons: so this vessel contained ten thousand gallons.\f*
\v 27 And he made ten brazen feet, of four cubits in length every foot, and four cubits in breadth, and three cubits in height.
\v 28 And the very work itself of the feet, was entergraven: and entergravings between the jointures.
\v 29 And between the little crowns and the plaits, lions, and oxen, and Cherubs: and in the jointures likewise above: and under the lions & oxen as it were bands of brass hanging down.
\v 30 And four wheels at every foot, and axletrees of brass: and at four sides as it were little shoulders under the lavatory cast, looking one against another.
\v 31 The mouth also of the lavatory was inward in the top of the head: and that which appeared outward, was of one cubit all round, and together it had one cubit and a half: and in the corners of the pillars were diverse engravings: and the middle enterpillars square not round.
\v 32 The four wheels also which were at the four corners of a foot, joined one to another under the foot: one wheel had in height a cubit and a half.
\v 33 And they were such wheels as are accustomed to be made in a chariot: and their axletrees and spokes, and strakes, and naves, all cast.
\v 34 For those four little shoulders also at every corner of one foot, were cast out of the foot and joined together.
\v 35 And in the top of the foot was a certain roundness of half a cubit, so wrought, that the lavatory might be put thereon, having the engravings thereof, and diverse carvings of it-self.
\v 36 He graved also in those ceilings, which were of brass, and in the corners, cherubs, and lions, and palmtrees, as it were in the similitude of a man standing, that they seemed not to be engraven, but put to round about.
\v 37 After this manner made he ten feet, of one casting and measure, and like graving.
\v 38 He made also ten lavatories of brass: one lavatory contained forty bates, and it was of four cubits: also at every foot, that is ten, he put so many lavatories.
\v 39 And he set the ten feet, five on the right side of the temple, and five on the left: and the sea he put on the right side of the temple against the East toward the South.
\v 40 Hiram therefore made cauldrons, and shovels, & little pots, and perfected all the work of king Salomon in the temple of our Lord.
\v 41 Two pillars, and two cords of the little heads upon the little heads of the pillars: and two little nets, to cover the two cords, that were over the heads of the pillars.
\v 42 And four hundred pomegranates in the two nets: two rews of pomegranates in every net, to cover the cords of the little heads, which were upon the heads of the pillars.
\v 43 And ten feet, and ten lavatories upon the feet.
\v 44 And one sea, and twelve oxen under the sea.
\v 45 And cauldrons, & shovels, and little pots. All the vessels that Hiram made to king Salomon in the house of our Lord, were of bright latten.
\v 46 In the champion country of Jordan did the king cast those things in a clay ground, between Socoth & Sarthan.
\v 47 And Salomon placed all the vessels: but for the exceeding great multitude the brass could not be weighed.
\v 48 And Salomon made all the vessels in the house of our Lord: an altar of gold, and a table, whereupon the loaves of proposition should be put, of gold:
\v 49 and candlesticks of gold, five on the right hand, and five on the left against the oracle, of pure gold: and as it were little flowers, and lamps above of gold: and golden snuffers,
\v 50 and water pots, and fleshhooks, and phials, and mortars, and censers, of most pure gold: and the hinges of doors of the inner Sanctum Sanctorum, and of the doors of the house of the temple, were of gold.
\v 51 And Salomon perfected all the work that he did in the house of our Lord, and brought in the things that David his father had sanctified, silver and gold, and the vessels, and laid them in the treasures of the house of our Lord. \f + \fr 7:51 \ft Had designed & dedicated to holy uses.\f*
\c 8
\p
\v 1 Then were gathered together all the ancients of Israel with the princes of the tribes, and the heads of the families of the children of Israel to king Salomon into Jerusalem: that they might carry the Ark of the covenant of our Lord out of the city of David, that is, out of Sion.
\v 2 And all Israel assembled to king Salomon in the month of Ethanim, on a solemn day, that is the seventh month.
\v 3 And all the ancients of Israel came, and the Priests took the ark,
\v 4 and carried the ark of our Lord, and the tabernacle of covenant, and all the vessels of the Sanctuary, that were in the tabernacle: and the Priests and the Levites carried them.
\v 5 And King Salomon, and all the multitude of Israel which was assembled unto him, went with him before the ark, and they immolated sheep and oxen without estimation and number.
\v 6 And the priests brought in the ark of the covenant of our Lord into his place, into the oracle of the temple, into Sanctum Sanctorum under the wings of the Cherubs.
\v 7 For the Cherubs spread their wings over the place of the ark, and covered the ark, and the bars thereof above.
\v 8 And whereas the bars stood out, and the ends of them appeared without in the Sanctuary before the oracle, they appeared no farther outward, which also were there until this present day.
\v 9 And in the ark there was nothing else but two tables of stone, which Moyses put in it in Horeb, when our Lord made the covenant with the children of Israel, when they came out of the Land of Ægypt. \f + \fr 8:9 \ft There was no more within the ark, Deut. 10. but on the out side was the rod of Aaron, Nu. 17. Heb. 9. the golden pot with Manna, Exod. 16. Heb. 9. and the book of the law repeated by Moyses, Deut. 31.\f*
\v 10 And it came to pass, when the Priests were gone out of the Sanctuary, a cloud filled the house of our Lord,
\v 11 and the Priests could not stand and minister for the cloud: for the glory of our Lord had filled the house of our Lord.
\v 12 Then said Salomon: Our Lord said that he would dwell in a cloud.
\v 13 Building I have built a house for thy habitation, thy most firm throne for ever.
\v 14 And the king turned his face, and blessed all the Church of Israel: for all the Church of Israel stood. \f + \fr 8:14 \ft Princes bless their people and parents their children.\f*
\v 15 And Salomon said: Bless be our Lord the God of Israel, who spake by his mouth to David my father, & in his own hands hath perfected it, saying:
\v 16 Since the day that I brought my people Israel out of Ægypt, I chose no city of all the tribes of Israel, that a house might be built, and my name might be there: but I chose David to be over my people Israel.
\v 17 And David my father would have built a house to the name of our Lord the God of Israel:
\v 18 and our Lord said to David my father: In that thou hast thought in thy heart to build a house to my name, thou hast done well, casting this same thing in thy mind.
\v 19 Nevertheless thou shalt not build me a house, but thy son, that shall come forth of thy reins, he shall build a house to my name.
\v 20 Our Lord hath confirmed his word, which he spake: & I stand for David my father, & sit upon the throne of Israel, as our Lord hath spoken: and I have built a house to the name of our Lord the God of Israel.
\v 21 And I have appointed there a place for the ark, wherein the covenant of our Lord is, which he made with our fathers, when they came out of the Land of Ægypt.
\v 22 And Salomon stood before the altar of our Lord in the sight of the assembly of Israel, and extended his hands toward heaven,
\v 23 and said: Lord God of Israel, there is no God like to thee in heaven above, and upon the earth beneath: which keepest covenant and mercy with thy servants, that walk before thee in all their heart.
\v 24 Which hast kept to thy servant David my father, the things that thou hast spoken to him: by mouth thou didst speak, and with thy hands thou hast accomplished, as this day proveth.
\v 25 Now therefore Lord God of Israel, keep unto thy servant David my father the things which thou hast spoken to him, saying: There shall not be taken away of thee a man before me, which sitteth upon the throne of Israel: yet so if thy children shall keep their way, that they walk before me as thou hast walked in my sight. \f + \fr 8:25 \ft Salomon knew well God's conditional promise, but persevered not in keeping his commandments, and therefore a great part of the Kingdom was taken from his children, yet the right of the Kingdom of Juda remained to his seed even to Christ our Saviour.\f*
\v 26 And now Lord God of Israel, let thy words be established, which thou hast spoken to thy servant David my father.
\v 27 Is it then to be thought that indeed God dwelleth upon the earth? For if heaven, and the heavens of heavens cannot contain thee, how much more this house, which I have built?
\v 28 But look toward the prayer of thy servant, & to his petitions, o Lord my God: hear the hymn and the prayer, which thy servant prayeth before thee this day:
\v 29 that thy eyes be opened upon this house night and day: upon the house, whereof thou saidst: My name shall be there: that thou hear the prayer, which thy servant prayeth in this place to thee.
\v 30 That thou hear the request of thy servant & of thy people Israel, whatsoever they shall pray for in this place, & thou shalt hear in the place of thy habitation in heaven: and when thou hast heard, thou shalt be merciful,
\v 31 If a man shall sin against his neighbour, & shall have any oath, wherewith he is held fast bound: & shall come because of the oath before thine altar into thy house,
\v 32 thou shalt hear in heaven: and shalt do, and judge thy servants, condemning the impious, and rendering his way upon his head, and justifying the just, and rewarding him according to his justice. \f + \fr 8:32 \ft Reward of good works.\f*
\v 33 If thy people Israel shall fly their enemies (because they will sin against thee) & doing penance and confessing to thy name, shall come, and pray, & beseech thee in this house;
\v 34 hear in heaven, & forgive the sin of thy people Israel, and thou shalt reduce them unto the land, which thou gavest to their fathers.
\v 35 If the heaven shall be shut, and it rain not, because of their sins, and praying in this place, they do penance to thy name, and shall be converted from their sins through their affliction:
\v 36 hear them in heaven, and forgive the sins of thy servants, and of thy people Israel: and shew them a good way wherein they may walk, and give rain upon thy land, which thou has given to thy people in possession.
\v 37 If famine arise in the land, or pestilence, or corrupt air, or blasting, or locust, or rust, and their enemy afflict them besieging the gates, all plague, all infirmity,
\v 38 all cursing, and banning, that shall chance to any man of thy people Israel: if any man shall know the wound of his heart, and shall spread forth his hands in this house,
\v 39 thou shalt hear in heaven, in the place of thy habitation, and shalt be merciful again, and shalt so do that thou give to every one according to his ways, as thou shalt see his heart (for thou only knowest the heart of all the children of men)
\v 40 that they fear thee all the days, which they live upon the face of the land, which thou hast given our fathers.
\v 41 Moreover also the stranger, which is not of thy people Israel, when he shall come from a far country for thy name (for thy great name shall be heard of, and thy strong hand,
\v 42 and thy stretched out arm every-where) when therefore he shall come, and shall pray in this place,
\v 43 thou shalt hear in heaven, in the firmament of thy habitation, & thou shalt do all things, for the which the stranger shall invocate thee: that all the peoples of the earth may learn to fear thy name, as thy people Israel, and may prove that thy name is invocated upon this house, which I have built.
\v 44 If thy people shall go forth to war against their enemies, by the way, whithersoever thou shalt send them, they shall pray to thee against the way of the city, which thou hast chosen, and against the house, which I have built to thy name,
\v 45 and thou shall hear in heaven their prayers, and their petitions, and shall do judgment for them.
\v 46 But if they shall sin to thee (for there is no man which sinneth not) and thou being wrath shalt deliver them to their enemies, and they shall be led captive into the land of their enemies far or near,
\v 47 and shall do penance in their heart in the place of captivity, and converted shall beseech thee in their captivity, saying: We have sinned, we have done wickedly, we have dealt impiously: \f + \fr 8:47 \ft External works of penance, except they proceed from the heart, suffice not for remission of sin.\f*
\v 48 and shall return to thee in all their heart, and all their soul, in the land of their enemies, to the which they shall be led captive: and shall pray to thee against the way of their land, which thou gavest to their fathers, & of the city which thou hast chosen, & of the temple which I have built to thy name:
\v 49 thou shalt hear in heaven, in the firmament of thy throne their prayers, and their petitions, and shall do their judgment for them:
\v 50 and shalt be merciful to thy people, which sinned to thee, and to all their iniquities wherewith they have transgressed against thee: & thou shalt give mercy before them that shall have them captives, that they may have compassion on them.
\v 51 For they are thy people, and thine inheritance, whom thou hast brought out of the Land of Ægypt, from the midst of the iron furnace.
\v 52 That thy eyes be open to the petition of thy servant, & of thy people Israel, and thou hear them in all things for which they shall invocate thee.
\v 53 For thou hast separated them to thee for an inheritance from all the peoples of the earth, as thou hast spoken by Moyses thy servant, when thou didst bring our fathers out of Ægypt, Lord God.
\v 54 And it came to pass, when Salomon had accomplished praying to our Lord all this prayer and petition, he rose from the sight of the altar of our Lord: for he had fastened both knees on the ground, and had spread his hands toward heaven.
\v 55 He stood therefore and blessed all the assembly of Israel with a loud voice, saying:
\v 56 Blessed be our Lord, which hath given rest to his people Israel, according to all things that he hath spoken: there hath not failed so much as one word of all the good things, that he spake by Moyses his servant.
\v 57 Be our Lord God with us, as he hath been with our fathers, not forsaking, nor rejecting us.
\v 58 But incline he our hearts to him, that we may walk in all his ways, and keep his commandments, and his ceremonies, and judgments whatsoever he commanded our fathers.
\v 59 And be these my words, wherewith I have prayed before our Lord, approaching to our Lord God day and night, that he may do judgment for his servant, and for his people Israel day by day:
\v 60 that all the people of the earth may know, that our Lord he is God, and there is none other besides him.
\v 61 Let our heart also be perfect with our Lord God, that we walk in his decrees, and keep his commandments, as also this day.
\v 62 Therefore the king, and all Israel with him, did immolate victims before our Lord.
\v 63 And Salomon killed pacific hosts, which he immolated to our Lord, of oxen two and twenty thousand, and of sheep an hundred twenty thousand: and they dedicated the temple of our Lord, the king, and the children of Israel.
\v 64 In that day the king sanctified the midst of the court, that was before the house of our Lord: for he made the holocaust there, and sacrifice, and fat of the pacifics: because the brazen altar, that was before our Lord, was too little, and could not take the holocaust, and sacrifice, and fat of the pacifics.
\v 65 Salomon therefore made in the time a solemn festivity, and all Israel with him, a great multitude from the entrance of Emath unto the River of Ægypt, before our Lord God, seven days and seven days, that is, fourteen days.
\v 66 And in the eighth day he dismissed the people: Who blessing the king, went into their tabernacles rejoicing, and with a joyful heart for all the good things, that our Lord had done to David his servant, and to Israel his people.
\c 9
\p
\v 0 twenty cities of Salomon, but liketh them not. 14. \add Salomon buildeth more cities and towns. 20. Maketh diverse nations tributary. 24. The Queen repaireth to her house. 25. The king offereth victims thrice every year. 26. And fetcheth gold from Ophir.\add*
\v 1 And it came to pass when Salomon had perfected the building of the house of our Lord, & the king's house, and all that he wished & would have done,
\v 2 our Lord appeared to him the second time, as he had appeared to him in Gabaon.
\v 3 And our Lord said to him: I have heard thy prayer & thy petition which thou hast prayed before me: I have sanctified this house, which thou hast built, that I might put my name there for ever, and mine eyes and my heart shall be there always.
\v 4 Thou also if thou wilt walk before me, as thy father walked, in simplicity of heart, and in equity, and wilt do all things, which I have commanded thee, and wilt keep my ordinances and my judgments: \f + \fr 9:4 \ft External worship is not acceptable to God, except it proceed from internal sincerity and devotion. Wherefore S. Augustin saith: God is worshipped in faith, hope, and charity. Enchirid. c. 3.\f*
\v 5 I will set the throne of thy Kingdom over Israel for ever, as I have spoken to David thy father, saying: There shall not be taken away a man of thy stock from the throne of Israel.
\v 6 But if by revolting you and your children shall turn away, not following me, nor keeping my commandments, and my ceremonies, which I have proposed to you, but shall go and worship strange gods, and adore them:
\v 7 I will take away Israel from the face of the land, which I have given them, and the temple which I have sanctified to my name, I will cast away from my sight, and Israel shall be for a proverb, and for a fable to all peoples.
\v 8 And this house shall be for an example: every one that shall pass by it, shall wonder, and hiss, and say: Why hath the Lord done thus to this land, and to this house?
\v 9 And they shall answer: Because they have forsaken the Lord their God, which brought their fathers out of the Land of Ægypt, and have followed strange gods, and adored them, and worshipped them: therefore hath the Lord brought upon them all this evil.
\v 10 And twenty years being complete, after that Salomon had built the two houses, that is, the house of our Lord, and the house of the king,
\v 11 (Hiram the king of Tyre ministering to Salomon cedar trees & fir trees, and gold according to all that he had need) then Salomon gave to Hiram twenty towns in the Land of Galilee. \f + \fr 9:11 \ft Salomon did not sell these cities, for he could not alienate them, but let the King of Tyre have the use and revenues in payment for timber, & for the gold which he sent.\f*
\v 12 And Hiram went from Tyre, to see the towns which Salomon had given him, and they pleased him not,
\v 13 and he said: Are these the cities, which thou hast given me, brother? And he called them the land Chabul, until this day. \f + \fr 9:13 \ft * dirty or displeasing.\f*
\v 14 Hiram also sent to king Salomon an hundred and twenty talents of gold.
\v 15 This is the sum of the expenses, which king Salomon offered to build the house of our Lord, and his own house, and Mello, and the wall of Jerusalem, and Heser, and Mageddo, and Gazer.
\v 16 Pharao the king of Ægypt came up and took Gazer, and burnt it with fire: And the Chananite, that dwelt in the city, he slew, and gave it for a dowry to his daughter the wife of Salomon.
\v 17 Salomon therefore built Gazer, and Bethhoron the lower,
\v 18 and Balaath, and Palmira in the Land of the wilderness.
\v 19 And all the villages, that pertained to him, and were without wall, he fenced, and the cities of the chariots, and the cities of the horsemen, and whatsoever pleased him to build in Jerusalem, and in Libanus, and in all the land of his dominion.
\v 20 All the people, that was remaining of the Amorrheites, and Hetheites, and Pherezites, and Heveites, and Jebusites, that are not of the children of Israel:
\v 21 their children, that were remaining in the land, to wit, those whom the children of Israel could not abolish: Salomon made tributaries, until this day.
\v 22 But of the children of Israel Salomon appointed not any man to serve, but they were men of war, and his servants, and Princes, and captains, and overseers of the chariots and horses.
\v 23 And there were Princes over all the works of Salomon, made overseers, five hundred fifty, which had the people subject, and commanded over their appointed works.
\v 24 And the daughter of Pharao went up out of the city of David into her house, which Salomon had built her: then did he build Mello.
\v 25 Salomon also offered three times every year holocausts, and pacific victims upon the altar, which he had built to our Lord, and he burnt incense before our Lord: and the temple was perfected.
\v 26 King Salomon also made a navy in Asiongaber, which is beside Ailath in the shore of the Redsea in the Land of Idumea.
\v 27 And Hiram sent in that navy his men, that were mariners & skillful of the sea, with the servants of Salomon.
\v 28 Who when they were come into Ophir, the gold taken thence of four hundred and twenty talents, they brought to king Salomon.
\c 10
\p
\v 1 But the queen of Saba also having heard the fame of Salomon, in the name of our Lord came to prove him in hard propositions. \f + \fr 10:1 \ft Part of Arabia is called Saba, near to Jury, but this Saba is beyond Arabia, as S. Hierom testifieth in Esaie 60. li. 17. it seemeth to be in Æthiopia: for our Saviour saith Mat. 12. The Queen of the South came from the ends of the earth, to hear the wisdom of Salomon.\f* \f + \fr 10:1 \ft * A wonderful thing, that a Queen upon fame of a man's wisdom travelled so far to hear him speak, and to see his government. But it was God's inspiration to signify by this figure, that the Church of Christ should be gathered of the Gentiles in all nations. Kings, Queens and most potent Princes also submitting themselves to Christ. Isaie 49.\f*
\v 2 And entering into Jerusalem with a great train, and riches, and camels carrying spices, and gold exceeding infinite, and precious stones, she came to king Salomon, and spake to him all things that she had in her heart.
\v 3 And Salomon interpreted to her all the words, that she proposed: there was not a word, that the king could be ignorant of, and could not answer her.
\v 4 And the queen of Saba seeing all the wisdom of Salomon, and the house which he had built,
\v 5 and the meats of his table, and the habitations of his servants, and the orders of them that served, and their garments, cup-bearers, and the holocausts which he offered in the house of our Lord: she had no longer spirit, \f + \fr 10:5 \ft As this Queen had no spirit, when she saw Salomon's wisdom, so the Church gathered of gentiles knowing Christ's grace, & finding the masters of Evangelical doctrine, casting away the spirit of pride, and laying off all haughtiness of mind, learned to distrust in herself, and to trust in the great mercy of her King. S. Greg. in Psal. 7. pæniten. to. 2.\f*
\v 6 and she said to the king: The report is true, which I have heard in my country,
\v 7 concerning thy words, and concerning thy wisdom, and I did not believe them that told me, till myself came, and saw with mine eyes, & have proved that the half hath not been told me: greater is thy wisdom, and thy works, than the rumour, which I have heard.
\v 8 Blessed are thy men, and blessed are thy servants, which stand before thee always, and hear thy wisdom.
\v 9 Be the Lord thy God blessed, whom thou hast pleased, and that hath set thee upon the throne of Israel, for that the Lord hath loved Israel for ever, and hath appointed thee king, to do judgment and justice.
\v 10 She therefore gave to the king an hundred and twenty talents of gold, and spices exceeding much, and precious stones: There was no more brought so much spice, as that which the queen of Saba gave to king Salomon.
\v 11 (But the navy also of Hiram, which carried gold out of Ophir, brought from Ophir thyine trees exceeding many, and precious stones.
\v 12 And the king made of the thyine trees the porches of the house of our Lord, and of the king's house, and harps & vials for the singers: there were not such thyine trees brought, nor seen until this present day.
\v 13 And king Salomon gave to the queen of Saba all that she would, and asked of him: beside those things, which of himself he offered her for a royal gift. Who returned, and went into her country with her servants.
\v 14 And the weight of the gold, that was brought to Salomon every year, was of six hundred sixty six talents of gold:
\v 15 beside that, which the men brought, that were over the tributes, and merchants, and all that sold light wares, and all the kings of Arabia, and the Dukes of the land.
\v 16 Salomon also made two hundred shields of most pure gold, six hundred sicles of gold did he allow for the plates of one shield.
\v 17 And three hundred targets of tried gold: and three hundred pounds of gold garnished one target: and the king put them in the house of the forest of Libanus.
\v 18 King Salomon also made a great throne of ivory: and covered it with gold exceeding yellow,
\v 19 which had six steps: and the top of the throne was round in the hinder part: and two hands on either side holding the seat: and two lions stood at every hand.
\v 20 And twelve little lions standing upon the six steps on either side: there was not such a work made in all Kingdoms.
\v 21 Yea and all the vessels, out of the which king Salomon drunk, were of gold: and all the furniture of the house of the forest of Libanus of most pure gold: there was no silver, neither was it thought of any price in the days of Salomon,
\v 22 because the king's navy, once in three years, went with the navy of Hiram on the sea into Tharsis, bringing thence gold, & silver, & the teeth of elephants, and apes, & peacocks.
\v 23 King Salomon therefore was magnified above all the kings of the earth in riches, & wisdom.
\v 24 And all the earth desired to see Salomon's face, that they might hear his wisdom, which God had given in his heart.
\v 25 And every one presented him gifts, vessels of silver and gold, garments, and instruments for war, spices also, and horses, and mules every year.
\v 26 And Salomon gathered together the chariots and horsemen, and there amounted to him a thousand four hundred chariots, and twelve thousand horsemen: and he disposed them in fenced cities, and with the king in Jerusalem.
\v 27 And he made that there was as great aboundance of silver in Jerusalem, as of stones: and of cedar trees he caused such a multitude, as if it were sycamore trees, which grow in the plains.
\v 28 And there were horses brought for Salomon out of Ægypt, and Coa, for the king's merchants bought them out of Coa, and brought them at a set price.
\v 29 And a chariot of four horses came out of Ægypt, for six hundred sicles of silver, and one horse for an hundred and fifty. And after this manner did all the kings of the Hetheites, and of Syria sell horses.
\c 11
\p
\v 1 And king Salomon loved many women strangers, the daughter also of Pharao, and Moabites, & Ammonites, Idumeians, and Sidonians, & Hetheians:
\v 2 of the nations, whereof our Lord said to the children of Israel: You shall not go in unto them, neither shall any of them come in unto yours: for they will most certainly turn away your hearts to follow their gods. To these therefore was Salomon coupled in most fervent love.
\v 3 And he had wives as it were queens seven hundred, and concubines three hundred: and the women turned away his heart. \f + \fr 11:3 \ft Though plurality of wives was then allowed, yet it was forbid to multiply many. Deut. 17.\f*
\v 4 And when he was now old, his heart was depraved by women, that he followed strange gods: neither was his heart perfect with our Lord his God, as the heart of David his father.
\v 5 But Salomon worshipped Astarthee the goddess of the Sidonians, and Moloch the idol of the Ammonites.
\v 6 And Salomon did that which was not liked before our Lord, and he accomplished not to follow our Lord, as David his father.
\v 7 Then built Salomon a temple to Chamos the idol of Moab, in the mount that is against Jerusalem, and to Moloch the idol of the children of Ammon.
\v 8 And in this manner did he to all his wives that were strangers, which burnt frankincense, & immolated to their gods.
\v 9 Therefore our Lord was wrath with Salomon, because his mind was turned away from our Lord the God of Israel, who had appeared unto him the second time,
\v 10 and had commanded him concerning this word, that he should not follow strange gods, & he kept not the things which our Lord commanded him.
\v 11 Our Lord therefore said to Salomon: Because thou hast done this, and hast not kept my covenant, and my precepts, which I have commanded thee, breaking I will rent asunder thy Kingdom, and will give it to thy servant.
\v 12 Nevertheless in thy days I will not do it because of David thy father: out of the hand of thy son I will rent it,
\v 13 neither will I take away the whole Kingdom, but one tribe I will give to thy son for David my servant, and Jerusalem, which I have chosen. \f + \fr 11:13 \ft The tribe of Juda.\f* \f + \fr 11:13 \ft By Jerusalem is understood the tribe of Benjamin, wherein it stood: so there remained two tribes to Salomon's heirs.\f*
\v 14 And our Lord raised up an adversary to Salomon, Adad an Idumeite of the king's seed, who was in Edom.
\v 15 For when David was in Idumea, and Joab the general of the warfare was gone up to bury them that were slain, and had slain all male kind in Idumea,
\v 16 for Joab tarried there six months, and all Israel, till he slew all male kind in Idumea.
\v 17 Adad himself fled, & the men of Idumea of his father's servants with him, to go into Ægypt: and Adad was a little boy.
\v 18 And when they rose out of Madian, they came into Pharan, and they took with them men of Pharan, and entered into Ægypt to Pharao the king of Ægypt: who gave him a house, and appointed him meats, and assigned him land.
\v 19 And Adad found grace before Pharao exceedingly, in so much that he gave him to wife the german sister of his wife Taphnes the queen.
\v 20 And the sister of Taphnes bare him a son Genubath, and Taphnes brought him up in the house of Pharao: & Genubath was dwelling at Pharao's house with his children.
\v 21 And when Adad in Ægypt had heard, that David slept with his fathers, and that Joab the general of the warfare was dead, he said to Pharao: Dismiss me, that I may go into my country.
\v 22 And Pharao said to him: For what lackest thou with me: that thou seekest to go into thine own country? But he answered: Nothing: yet I beseech thee that thou dismiss me.
\v 23 God also raised up to him an adversary, Razon the son of Eliada, who had fled Adarezer the king of Soba his Lord:
\v 24 and he gathered men against him, and he became the captain of thieves, when David killed them: and they went to Damascus, and dwelt there, and they made him king in Damascus,
\v 25 and he was an adversary to Israel all the days of Salomon: and this is the evil of Adad, and hatred against Israel, and he reigned in Syria. \f + \fr 11:25 \ft From the time that Salomon fell to idolatry, he was more impugned by three perpetual adversaries, Adad, Razon, and Hieroboam; mystically signifying the flesh, the world, and the devil.\f*
\v 26 Jeroboam also the son of Nabath, an Ephratheite of Sareda, the servant of Salomon, whose mother was called Serva, a woman widow, lifted up his hand against the king.
\v 27 And this is the cause of his rebellion against him, because Salomon built Mello, and filled up the breach of the city of David his father.
\v 28 And Jeroboam was a strong man and mighty: and Salomon seeing the young man of a good wit and industrious, had made him chief over the tributes of all the house of Joseph.
\v 29 It came to pass therefore at that time, that Jeroboam went out of Jerusalem, and the Prophet Ahias the Silonite found him in the way, covered with a new cloak: and they two only were in the field.
\v 30 And Ahias taking his new cloak, wherewith he was covered, cut it into twelve parts. \f + \fr 11:30 \ft This fact confirmed his words, that he spake seriously and feigned not.\f*
\v 31 And he said to Jeroboam: Take unto thee ten pieces: for thus saith our Lord the God of Israel: Behold I will rent the Kingdom out of the hand of Salomon, and will give thee ten tribes.
\v 32 But one tribe shall remain to him for my servant David, and Jerusalem the city, which I have chosen of all the tribes of Israel:
\v 33 because he hath forsaken me, and hath adored Astarthee the goddess of the Sidonians, and Chamos the god of Moab, and Moloch the god of the children of Ammon: and hath not walked in my ways, to do justice before me, and my precepts, and judgments, as David his father.
\v 34 Neither will I take away all the Kingdom out of his hand, but I will make him Prince all the days of his life, for David my servant, whom I chose, who kept my commandments & my precepts.
\v 35 But I will take away the Kingdom out of his son's hand, and will give thee ten tribes:
\v 36 and to his son I will give one tribe, that there may remain a lamp to David my servant at all times before me in Jerusalem, the city which I have chosen, that my name might be there.
\v 37 And thee will I take, and thou shalt reign over all things, that thy soul desireth, and thou shalt be king over Israel.
\v 38 If therefore thou wilt hear all things, that I shall command thee, and wilt walk in my ways, and do that which is right before me, keeping my commandments and my precepts, as David my servant did: I will be with thee, and will build thee a faithful house, as I built a house to David, and I will deliver Israel to thee:
\v 39 and I will afflict the seed of David upon this, but yet not always.
\v 40 Salomon therefore would have killed Jeroboam: who arose, and fled into Ægypt to Sesac the king of Ægypt, and was in Ægypt until the death of Salomon.
\v 41 And the rest of the words of Salomon, and all that he did, and his wisdom: behold they are all written in the Book of the words of the days of Salomon.
\v 42 And the days that Salomon reigned in Jerusalem over all Israel, are forty years.
\v 43 And Salomon slept with his fathers, and was buried in the city of David his father, & Roboam his son reigned for him. \f + \fr 11:43 \ft Whether he repented and was saved or no, is uncertain.\f*
\c 12
\p
\v 1 And Roboam came into Sichem: for thither was all Israel gathered together to make him king. \f + \fr 12:1 \ft The third part. The division of the Kingdom, Several reigns of certain Kings: and preaching of special Prophets.\f*
\v 2 But Jeroboam the son of Nabat, when he was yet in Ægypt fugitive from the face of king Salomon, hearing of his death; returned out of Ægypt.
\v 3 And they sent and called him: Jeroboam therefore came, and all the multitude of Israel, and they spake to Roboam, saying.
\v 4 Thy father laid a most hard yoke upon us: thou therefore diminish now a little of thy father's most hard empire, and of the most heavy yoke, that he laid upon us, and we will serve thee.
\v 5 Who said to them: Go until the third day, and return to me. And when the people was gone,
\v 6 King Roboam took counsel with the ancients, that assisted before Salomon his father, whiles he yet lived, and he said: What counsel do you give me, that I may answer this people?
\v 7 Who said to him: If this day thou wilt yield to this people, and condescend to them, and grant to their petition, & wilt speak to them gentle words, they will be thy servants always.
\v 8 Who left the counsel of the ancients, which they had given him, and admitted youngmen, that had been brought up with him, & waited on him,
\v 9 and he said to them: What counsel give you me, that I may answer this people, which have said to me: Make the yoke lighter which thy father hath put upon us?
\v 10 And the youngmen that had been brought up with him, said: Thus speak to this people, which have spoken to thee, saying: Thy father aggravated our yoke, do thou ease it. Thus shalt thou speak to them: My least finger is grosser than the back of my father.
\v 11 And now my father laid upon you a heavy yoke, but I will add upon your yoke: my father beat you with scourges, but I will beat you with scorpions.
\v 12 Jeroboam therefore came, and all the people to Roboam the third day, as the king had spoken, saying: Return to me the third day.
\v 13 And the king answered the people rough words, leaving the counsel of the ancients, which they had given him,
\v 14 and he spake to them according to the counsel of the youngmen, saying: My father made your yoke heavy, but I will add to your yoke: my father beat you with whips, but I will beat you with scorpions.
\v 15 And the king condescended not to the people: because our Lord was turned away from him, that he might raise up his word, which he had spoken in the hand of Ahias the Silonite, to Jeroboam the son of Nabat. \f + \fr 12:15 \ft This phrase noteth the sequel, not the final cause. As chap. 14. v. 9.\f*
\v 16 The people therefore seeing that the king would not hear them, answered him, saying: What part have we in David? Or what inheritance in the son of Isai? Go into thy tabernacles Israel, now see to thy house David. And Israel went into their tabernacles.
\v 17 But over the children of Israel, whosoever dwelt in the cities of Juda, Roboam reigned.
\v 18 King Roboam therefore sent Aduram, who was over the tributes: and all Israel stoned him, and he died, moreover king Roboam in haste went up into his chariot, and fled into Jerusalem:
\v 19 and Israel revolted from the house of David, until this present day.
\v 20 And it came to pass when all Israel had heard, that Jeroboam was returned, they sent, and called him, an assembly being gathered, and they made him king over all Israel, neither did any man follow the house of David beside the tribe of Juda only.
\v 21 And Roboam came to Jerusalem, and gathered together all the house of Juda, and the tribe of Benjamin, an hundred fourscore thousand chosen men warriors, to fight against the house of Israel, and to reduce the kingdom to Roboam the son of Salomon.
\v 22 But the word of our Lord came to Semeias the man of God, saying:
\v 23 Speak to Roboam the son of Salomon, the king of Juda, and to all the house of Juda, and Benjamin, and the rest of the people, saying:
\v 24 Thus saith our Lord: You shall not go up, neither shall you fight against your brethren the children of Israel: let every man return into his house, for this word is done by me. They heard the word of our Lord, & returned from their journey as our Lord had commanded them.
\v 25 And Jeroboam built Sichem in mount Ephraim, and dwelt there: and departing thence he built Phanuel.
\v 26 And Jeroboam said in his heart: Now will the Kingdom return to the house of David,
\v 27 if this people shall go up to make sacrifices in the house of our Lord into Jerusalem: and the heart of this people will be turned to their lord Roboam the king of Juda, and they will kill me, and return to him.
\v 28 And finding out a device he made two golden calves, and said to them: Go up no more into Jerusalem: Behold thy gods Israel, which brought thee out of the Land of Ægypt. \f + \fr 12:28 \ft Adevilish policy to make a religion conformable to the temporal state.\f*
\v 29 And he put one in Bethel, and the other in Dan:
\v 30 and this thing was an occasion of sin: for the people went to adore the calf, as far as Dan.
\v 31 And he made temples in the excelses, and Priests of the abjects of the people, which were not of the children of Levi. \f + \fr 12:31 \ft For such a religion such Priests were fittest.\f*
\v 32 And he appointed a solemn day in the eighth month, the fifteenth day of the month, after the similitude of the solemnity, that was celebrated in Juda. And going up he made in like manner an altar in Bethel, to immolate to the calves, which he had framed: and he ordained in Bethel priests of the excelses, which he had made. \f + \fr 12:32 \ft Places on hills, where they sacrificed calves, and other things to the images of calves.\f*
\v 33 And he went upon the altar, which he had built in Bethel, the fifteenth day of the eighth month, which he had forged out of his own heart: and he made a solemnity to the children of Israel, and went up upon the altar, to burn incense.
\c 13
\p
\v 1 And behold a man of God came out of Juda, in the word of our Lord into Bethel, Jeroboam standing upon the altar, and censing. \f + \fr 13:1 \ft This foreshewing long before the name of a child that should be born, importeth that he should do great things. See 4. Reg. 22.\f*
\v 2 And he cried out against the altar in the word of our Lord, and said: Altar, altar, thus saith our Lord: Behold a child shall be born to the house of David, named Josias, and he shall immolate upon thee priests of the excelses, which now do burn frankincense on thee, and he shall burn men's bones upon thee.
\v 3 And he gave a sign in that day, saying: This shall be the sign, that our Lord hath spoken: Behold the altar shall be cloven, and the ashes on it shall be poured out.
\v 4 And when the king had heard the word of the man of God, which he cried out against the altar in Bethel, he stretched forth his hand from the altar, saying: Take him. And his hand withered, which he stretched forth against him: neither was he able to draw it back upon him.
\v 5 The altar also was cloven, and the ashes were poured out of the altar, according to the sign which the man of God had told before in the word of our Lord.
\v 6 And the king said to the man of God: Beseech the face of our Lord thy God, and pray for me, that my hand may be restored me. And the man of God besought the face of our Lord, and the king's hand was restored to him, and it became as it was before.
\v 7 And the king spake to the man of God: Come home with me, that thou mayst dine, and I will give thee gifts.
\v 8 And the man of God answered the king: If thou wouldest give me the half part of thy house, I will not come with thee, nor eat bread, nor drink water in this place:
\v 9 for so was it enjoined in the word of our Lord commanding: Thou shalt not eat bread, nor drink water, nor return by the way that thou camest.
\v 10 He departed therefore by another way, and returned not by the way, that he came into Bethel.
\v 11 And a certain Prophet being old dwelt in Bethel, to whom his sons came and told him all the works, that the man of God had done that day in Bethel: and the words which he had spoken to the king, they told their father.
\v 12 And their father said to them: What way went he? His sons shewed him the way, by which the man of God was gone, which came out of Juda.
\v 13 And he said to his sons: Saddle me an ass. Who when they had saddled it, he got up,
\v 14 and went after the man of God, and found him sitting under a terebinth: and he said to him: Art thou the man of God that camest out of Juda? He answered: I am he.
\v 15 And he said to him: Come home with me, that thou mayst eat bread.
\v 16 Who said: I cannot return, nor come with thee, neither will I eat bread, nor drink water in this place:
\v 17 because our Lord spake to me in the word of our Lord, saying: Thou shalt not eat bread, and thou shalt not drink water there, nor return by the way thou wentest.
\v 18 Who said to him: I also am a Prophet like to thee: and an Angel hath spoken to me in the word of our Lord, saying: Bring him back with thee into thy house, that he may eat bread, and drink water. He deceived him, \f + \fr 13:18 \ft This man of Bethel was indeed a Prophet of God, but in this lied wickedly, and so deceiving the other Prophet, made him to break God's commandment, for which he was slain. Whereupon Hieroboam (whom the wicked Prophet sought to please) was less afraid to proceed in Idolatry.\f*
\v 19 and brought him back with him: he did eat therefore bread in his house, and drunk water.
\v 20 And when they sat at the table, the word of our Lord came to the Prophet, that brought him back.
\v 21 And he cried out to the man of God, which came out of Juda, saying: Thus saith our Lord: Because thou hast not been obedient to the mouth of our Lord, and hast not kept the commandment which our Lord thy God commanded thee,
\v 22 and hast returned, and eaten bread, and drunk water in the place wherein he commanded thee that thou shouldest not eat bread, nor drink water, thy dead body shall not be brought into the sepulchre of thy fathers.
\v 23 And when he had eaten and drunk, he saddled his ass for the Prophet, whom he brought back.
\v 24 Who when he was gone, a lion found him in the way, and killed him, and his body was cast forth in the way: and the ass stood by him, and the lion stood by the dead body. \f + \fr 13:24 \ft Not only the deceiver, but also he that is deceived, is guilty and punishable for breaking God's commandment.\f*
\v 25 And behold, men passing by saw the dead body cast in the way, and the lion standing beside the body. And they came and divulged it in the city, wherein that old Prophet dwelt.
\v 26 Which when that Prophet heard, which had brought him back out of the way, he said: It is the man of God, that was disobedient to the mouth of our Lord, and our Lord hath delivered him to the lion, & he hath torn him, and killed him according to the word of our Lord, that he spake to him.
\v 27 And he said to his sons: Saddle me an ass. Who when they had saddled,
\v 28 and he was gone, he found his dead body cast forth in the way, and the ass and the lion standing by the corpse: the lion did not eat of the dead body, nor hurt the ass. \f + \fr 13:28 \ft By this it appeareth to be God's work and punishment.\f*
\v 29 The Prophet therefore took the corpse of the man of God, and laid it upon the ass, and returning brought it into the city of the old Prophet, that they might mourn for him.
\v 30 And he laid his corpse in his own sepulchre: and they mourned for him: Alas, alas my brother.
\v 31 And when they had mourned for him, he said to his sons: When I shall be dead, bury me in the sepulchre, wherein the man of God is buried: beside his bones lay my bones.
\v 32 For assuredly the word shall come to pass, which he hath foretold in the word of our Lord against the altar that is in Bethel: and against all the temples of the excelses, that are in the cities of Samaria.
\v 33 After these words Jeroboam returned not from his wicked way, but on the contrary part he made of the most abject of the people Priests of the excelses: Whosoever would, he filled his hand, and he was made a Priest of the excelses.
\v 34 And for this cause did the house of Jeroboam sin, and was overthrown, and destroyed from the face of the earth.
\c 14
\p
\v 1 At that time Abia the son of Jeroboam was sick.
\v 2 And Jeroboam said to his wife: Arise, and change thy habit, that thou be not known to be the wife of Jeroboam, & go into Silo, where Ahias the Prophet is, which spake to me, that I should reign over this people.
\v 3 Take also in thy hand ten loaves, & cracknels, & a vessel of honey, & go to him: for he will shew thee what shall happen to this child.
\v 4 The wife of Jeroboam did as he had spoken: and rising up went into Silo, and came into the house of Ahias: but he could not see, because his eyes were dim for age.
\v 5 And our Lord said to Ahias: Behold the wife of Jeroboam cometh in, to consult thee concerning her son that is sick: thus and thus shalt thou speak to her. When she therefore entered in, and dissembled to be that she was,
\v 6 Ahias heard the sound of her feet entering in at the door, and said: Come in Jeroboam's wife: Why doest thou feign thyself to be another woman? But I am sent to thee a heavy messenger.
\v 7 Go, and tell Jeroboam: Thus saith our Lord the God of Israel: Because I have exalted thee out of the midst of the people, and made thee Prince over my people Israel,
\v 8 and have rent the Kingdom of the house of David, and given it to thee, and thou hast not been as my servant David, who kept my commandments; and followed me in all his heart, doing that which was well liked in my sight:
\v 9 but has wrought evil above all, that have been before thee, and hast made thee strange and molten gods, that thou mightest provoke me to anger, and hast rejected me behind thy back: \f + \fr 14:9 \ft Jeroboam did not wittingly and of purpose set up false gods, to the end he might provoke God to anger: for his intention only was to keep the people from going to Jerusalem, lest by that occasion they should return to Roboam their lord, King of Juda. ch. 12. v. 27. But by setting up idols he did provoke God consequently to anger. So here and in other places this phrase: that he might provoke: that it might be fulfilled, and the like, signifieth not the final cause, but the sequel of other facts, without direct intention.\f*
\v 10 therefore behold I will bring in evils upon the house of Jeroboam, and will strike of Jeroboam him that pisseth to the wall, and the inclosed, and the vilest in Israel: and I will cleanse the remains of the house of Jeroboam, as dung is wont to be cleansed till all be pure.
\v 11 They that shall die of Jeroboam in the city, them the dogs shall eat: and they that shall die in the field, them the fowls of the air shall devour: because our Lord hath spoken.
\v 12 Thou therefore arise, and go into thy house: and in the very entrance of thy feet into the city, the child shall die,
\v 13 & all Israel shall mourn for him, and shall bury him: for this only of Jeroboam shall be brought into the sepulchre, because upon him hath been found a good word from our Lord the God of Israel, in the house of Jeroboam.
\v 14 And our Lord will appoint to himself a king over Israel, that shall strike the house of Jeroboam in this day, and in this time:
\v 15 and our Lord the God of Israel shall strike it, as a reed is wont to be moved in the water: and he shall pluck out Israel from this good country, which he gave to their fathers, and shall scatter them over the River: because they have made to themselves groves, to provoke our Lord.
\v 16 And our Lord shall deliver Israel for the sins of Jeroboam, who hath sinned, and made Israel to sin.
\v 17 The wife therefore of Jeroboam arose, and departed, and came into Thersa: and when she entered the threshold of the house, the child died,
\v 18 and they buried him. And all Israel mourned for him according to the word of our Lord, which he spake in the hand of his servant Ahias the Prophet.
\v 19 But the rest of the words of Jeroboam, how he fought, and how he reigned, behold they are written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Israel.
\v 20 And the days, that Jeroboam reigned, are two and twenty years: and he slept with his fathers: and Nadab his son reigned for him.
\v 21 Moreover Roboam the son of Salomon reigned in Juda: one and forty years old was Roboam when he began to reign: seventeen years reigned he in Jerusalem the city, which our Lord chose to put his name there, of all the tribes of Israel. And his mother's name was Naama an Ammonite.
\v 22 And Judas did evil before our Lord, and provoked him above all things, that their fathers had done, in their sins which they sinned.
\v 23 For they also built them altars, & statues, & groves upon every high hill, and under every tree full of green leaves:
\v 24 yea and effeminates were in the land, and they did all the abominations of the gentiles, which our Lord destroyed before the face of the children of Israel.
\v 25 And in the fifth year of the reign of Roboam, Sesac the king of Ægypt came up into Jerusalem,
\v 26 and took the treasures of the house of our Lord, and the kings' treasures, and all things he spoiled: the shields also of gold, which Salomon had made:
\v 27 for the which Roboam made brazen shields, and delivered them into the hand of the captains of shield-bearers, and of them that kept watch before the door of the king's house.
\v 28 And when the king went into the house of our Lord, they that had the office to go before, carried them: and afterward they recarried them to the armoury of the shield-bearers.
\v 29 And the rest of the words of Roboam, and all that he did, behold they are written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Juda.
\v 30 And there was war between Roboam and Jeroboam always.
\v 31 And Roboam slept with his fathers, and was buried with them in the city of David: and his mother's name was Naama an Ammonite: and Abias his son reigned for him.
\c 15
\p
\v 1 Therefore in the eighteenth year of king Jeroboam the son of Nabat, Abias reigned over Juda.
\v 2 Three years reigned he in Jerusalem: the name of his mother was Maacha the daughter of Abessalom.
\v 3 And he walked in all the sins of his father, which he had done before him: neither was his heart perfect with our Lord his God, as the heart of David his father.
\v 4 But for David's sake our Lord his God gave him a lamp in Jerusalem, that he might raise up his son after him, and establish Jerusalem:
\v 5 because David had done right in the eyes of our Lord, & had not declined from all things, which he commanded him, all the days of his life, except the matter of Urias the Hetheite. \f + \fr 15:5 \ft David's posterity conserved for his sake.\f*
\v 6 But there was war between Roboam and Jeroboam all the time of his life.
\v 7 And the rest of the words of Abias, and all that he did, are they not written in the Book of the words of the kings of Juda? And there was war between Abias and Jeroboam.
\v 8 And Abias slept with his fathers, and they buried him in the city of David: and Asa his son reigned for him.
\v 9 In the twentieth year therefore of Jeroboam the king of Israel reigned Asa the king of Juda.
\v 10 And he reigned one and forty years in Jerusalem. His mother's name was Maacha, the daughter of Abessalom.
\v 11 And Asa did right before the sight of our Lord, as David his father:
\v 12 and he took away the effeminate out of the land, and he purged all the filth of the idols, which his fathers had made.
\v 13 Moreover he removed also Maacha his mother, that she should not be Princess in the sacrifice of Priapus, and in the grove which she had consecrated: and he destroyed her den, and brake the most filthy idol, and burnt it in the torrent cedron:
\v 14 but the excelses he did not take away. Otherwise the heart of Asa was perfect with our Lord all his days: \f + \fr 15:14 \ft Those altars which Salomon for his wives that were idolaters Asa destroyed not, but all which Roboam, and Abias had made, or suffered to be made for their own people, he pulled down. Josias afterward destroyed also those which Salomon had made. 2. Paral.\f*
\v 15 and he carried in those things, which his father had sanctified & vowed, into the house of our Lord, silver and gold, and vessels.
\v 16 And there was war between Asa and Baasa the king of Israel all their days.
\v 17 Baasa also the king of Israel went up into Juda, and built Rama, that no man might go out or come in of Asa's side the king of Juda.
\v 18 Asa therefore taking all the silver and gold that remained in the treasures of the house of our Lord, and in the treasures of the king's house, gave it into the hands of his servants: and he sent to Benadad the son of Tabremon the son of Hezion, the king of Syria, which dwelt in Damascus, saying:
\v 19 There is a league between me and thee, and betwixt my father and thy father: therefore I have sent thee gifts, silver and gold: and I desire thee that thou come, and make void the league, that thou hast with Baasa the king of Israel, and he may retire from me.
\v 20 Benadad agreeing to king Asa, sent the Princes of his army into the cities of Israel, and they struck Ahion, & Dan, & Abeldomum of Maacha, & all Cenneroth, to wit, all the Land of Nephthali.
\v 21 Which when Baasa had heard, he intermitted to build Rama, & returned into Thersa.
\v 22 But king Asa sent word into all Juda, saying: Let no man be excused, and they took stones from Rama, and the timber thereof, wherewith Baasa had built, & Asa of it built Gabaa Benjamin and Maspha.
\v 23 But the rest of all the words of Asa, & all his forces, & all that he did, & the cities that he built, are not these written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Juda? Howbeit in the time of his old age he was diseased in his feet.
\v 24 And he slept with his fathers, & was buried with them in the city of David his father. And Josaphat his son reigned for him.
\v 25 But Nadab the son of Jeroboam reigned over Israel the second year of Asa the king of Juda: and he reigned over Israel two years.
\v 26 And he did that which is evil in the sight of our Lord, & walked in the ways of his father, and in his sins, wherewith he made Israel to sin.
\v 27 And Baasa the son of Ahias of the house of Issachar, lay in wait against him, & struck him in Gebbethon, which is a city of the Philisthiims: for Nadab & all Israel besieged Gebbethon.
\v 28 Baasa therefore slew him in the third year of Asa the king of Juda, and reigned for him.
\v 29 And when he reigned, he struck all the house of Jeroboam: he left not so much as one soul of his seed, till he destroyed him according to the word of our Lord, which he had spoken in the hand of Ahias the Silonite, \f + \fr 15:29 \ft The author of schism punished in his posterity.\f*
\v 30 for the sins of Jeroboam, which he had sinned, & wherewith he had caused Israel to sin, and for the offence, wherewith he provoked our Lord the God of Israel.
\v 31 But the rest of the words of Nadab, and all that he wrought, are not these things written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Israel?
\v 32 And there was war between Asa and Baasa the king of Israel all their days.
\v 33 In the third year of Asa the king of Juda, reigned Baasa the son of Ahias over all Israel in Thersa four & twenty years.
\v 34 And he did evil before our Lord, and walked in the ways of Jeroboam, and in his sins, wherewith he made Israel to sin.
\c 16
\p
\v 1 And the word of our Lord came to Jehu the son of Hanani against Baasa, saying:
\v 2 For so much as I have exalted thee out of the dust, and set thee duke over my people Israel, but thou hast walked in the way of Jeroboam, and hast made my people Israel to sin, that thou mightest anger me with their sins:
\v 3 behold, I will cut down the posterity of Baasa, and the posterity of his house, and I will make thy house as the house of Jeroboam the son of Nabat.
\v 4 Whosoever of Baasa shall die in the city, him shall the dogs eat: and whosoever of his shall die in the country, him shall the fowls of the air devour.
\v 5 But the rest of the words of Baasa, and whatsoever he did, and his battles, are not these things written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Israel?
\v 6 Baasa therefore slept with his fathers, and was buried in Thersa: and Ela his son reigned for him.
\v 7 And when the word of our Lord came in the hand of Jehu the son of Hanani the Prophet against Baasa, and against his house, & against all the evil, that he had done before our Lord, to anger him in the works of his hands, that it should be made as the house of Jeroboam: for this cause he slew him, that is to say, Jehu the son of Hanani, the Prophet.
\v 8 In the six and twentieth year of Asa the king of Juda, reigned Ela the son of Baasa over Israel in Thersa two years.
\v 9 And his servant Zambri rebelled against him, the captain of the half part of the horsemen: and Ela was in Thersa drinking, and drunken in the house of Arsa the governor of Thersa.
\v 10 Zambri therefore rushing in, struck and slew him in the seven & twentieth year of Asa the king of Juda, and he reigned for him.
\v 11 And when he reigned, and sat upon his throne, he struck all the house of Baasa, and he left not of it one that could piss against a wall, and his kinsfolk and friends.
\v 12 And Zambri destroyed all the house of Baasa, according to the word of our Lord, that he had spoken to Baasa in the hand of Jehu the Prophet,
\v 13 for all the sins of Baasa, and the sins of Ela his son, who sinned, and made Israel to sin, provoking our Lord the God of Israel in their vanities.
\v 14 But the rest of the words of Ela, and all that he did, are not these written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Israel?
\v 15 In the seven and twentieth year of Asa the king of Juda, reigned Zambri seven days in Thersa: moreover the army besieged Gebbethon a city of the Philisthiims.
\v 16 And when they heard that Zambri had rebelled, and slain the king, all Israel made Amri their king, who was General of the warfare over Israel that day, in the camp. \f + \fr 16:16 \ft All those that were in the camp chose their General to be their King, and prevailed therein, though another half of Israel chose & followed another for a time.\f*
\v 17 Amri therefore went up, and all Israel with him from Gebbethon, and they besieged Thersa.
\v 18 And Zambri seeing that the city should be taken, he went into the palace, & burnt himself with the king's house: and he died
\v 19 in his sins, which he had sinned doing evil before our Lord, and walking in the way of Jeroboam, and in his sin, wherewith he made Israel to sin.
\v 20 But the rest of the words of Zambri, and of his treason, and tyranny, are not these things written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Israel?
\v 21 Then was the people of Israel divided into two parts: the half part of the people followed Thebni the son of Gineth, to make him king: & the half part Amri.
\v 22 But the people that was with Amri, prevailed over the people that followed Thebni the son of Gineth: and Thebni died, and Amri reigned.
\v 23 In the one and thirtieth year of Asa the king of Juda Amri reigned over Israel, twelve years: in Thersa he reigned six years. \f + \fr 16:23 \ft Thebni being then dead he reigned peaceably, for he began his reign the 17. year of Asa. v. 15. & 16. and reigned in all 12. years.\f*
\v 24 And he bought the mount of Samaria of Somer for two talents of silver: & he built it, and he called the city which he had built by the name of Semer the lord of the mount of Samaria.
\v 25 And Amri did evil in the sight of our Lord, & wrought wickedly above all, that were before him.
\v 26 And he walked in all the way of Jeroboam the son of Nabat, and in his sins wherewith he made Israel to sin: that they might anger our Lord the God of Israel in their vanities.
\v 27 But the rest of the words of Amri, and the battles he made, are not these things written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Israel?
\v 28 And Amri slept with his fathers, and was buried in Samaria, and Achab his son reigned for him.
\v 29 But Achab the son of Amri reigned over Israel the eight & thirtieth year of Asa the king of Juda. And Achab the son of Amri reigned over Israel in Samaria two and twenty years.
\v 30 And Achab the son of Amri did evil in the sight of our Lord above all that were before him.
\v 31 Neither did it suffice him that he walked in the sins of Jeroboam the son of Nabat: besides he took to wife Jezabel the daughter of Ethbaul the king of the Sidonians. And he went, and served Baal, and adored him.
\v 32 And he set an altar to Baal in the temple of Baal, which he had built in Samaria,
\v 33 and he planted a grove: and Achab added in his work, provoking our Lord the God of Israel above all the kings of Israel, that were before him.
\v 34 In his days Hiel of Bethel built Jericho: in Abiram his first born he founded it, and in Segub his last he set up the gates thereof: according to the word of our Lord, which he spake in the hand of Josue the son of Nun. \f + \fr 16:34 \ft When Hiel began to build Jericho, his eldest son died, so the rest successively, that the last died when he finished the building: because God by the mouth of Josue had forbid the building thereof.\f*
\c 17
\p
\v 1 And Elias the Thesbite of the inhabiters of Galaad said to Achab: Our Lord liveth the God of Israel, in whose sight I stand, if there shall be these years dew and rain, but according to the words of my mouth.
\v 2 And the word of our Lord came to him, saying:
\v 3 Depart from hence, and go against the East, and be hid in the Torrent Carith, which is against Jordan,
\v 4 and there thou shalt drink of the torrent: and I have commanded the ravens that they feed thee there.
\v 5 He therefore went, and did according to the word of our Lord: and when he was gone, he sat in the Torrent Carith, which is against Jordan.
\v 6 The ravens also brought him bread and flesh in the morning, in like manner bread and flesh in the evening, and he drank of the torrent.
\v 7 But after certain days the torrent was dried: for it had not rained upon the earth. \f + \fr 17:7 \ft The Epistle on Tuesday in the 2. week of Lent.\f*
\v 8 Therefore the word of our Lord came to him, saying:
\v 9 Arise, and go into Sareptha of the Sidonians, and thou shalt tarry there: for I have commanded a widow woman there to feed thee.
\v 10 He arose and went into Sareptha. And when he was come to the gate of the city, the widow woman appeared to him gathering sticks, and he called her, and said to her: Give me a little water in a vessel, that I may drink.
\v 11 And when she went to fetch it, he cried after her saying: Bring me also, I beseech thee, a morsel of bread in thy hand.
\v 12 who answered: Our Lord thy God liveth, I have no bread, but so much meal in a pot as a hand can hold, and a little oil in a vessel: behold I gather two sticks, that I may go in, and dress it for me & my son, that we may eat, and die. \f + \fr 17:12 \ft The Epistle on Friday in the 4. week of Lent.\f*
\v 13 To whom Elias said: fear not, but go, and do as thou hast said: but first make for me of the same meal a little hearth cake, & bring it to me: & for thyself & thy son thou shalt make afterward.
\v 14 For thus saith our Lord the God of Israel: The pot of meal shall not fail, nor the vessel of oil be diminished until the day, wherein our Lord will give rain upon the face of the earth.
\v 15 Who went and did according to the word of Elias: and he did eat, and she, and her house: and from that day
\v 16 the pot of meal failed not, and the vessel of oil was not diminished, according to the word of our Lord, which he spake in the hand of Elias.
\v 17 And it came to pass after these things, the son of the woman, the good wife of the house, fell sick, & the sickness was very vehement, so that there remained no breath in him,
\v 18 She therefore said to Elias: what is to me and thee thou man of God? Comest thou unto me, that mine iniquities might be remembered, and thou mightest kill my son?
\v 19 And Elias said to her: Give me thy son. And he took him from her bosom, and carried him into the upper chamber where himself abode, and laid him upon his bed.
\v 20 And he cried to our Lord, and said: O Lord my God, what, the widow also with whom I am after a sort sustained, hast thou afflicted, that thou wouldest kill her son? \f + \fr 17:20 \ft To this question (saith S. Augustin) the Prophet answered in spirit: No. For God killed not this child to afflict so good a mother, but to confirm her in true religion & comfort her by raising him from death. So Lazarus died not to remain dead, but to be raised to life, for God's more glory. Ioan. 11. v. 4. S. Aug. li. 2. q. 5. ad Simplicia.\f*
\v 21 And he stretched forth, and measured himself upon the child three times, and he cried to our Lord, and said: O Lord my God, let the soul of this child, I beseech thee, return into his body.
\v 22 And our Lord heard the voice of Elias: and the soul of the child returned into him, and he revived.
\v 23 And Elias took the child, and brought him down from the upper chamber into the lower house, and delivered him to his mother, and said to her: Behold thy son liveth.
\v 24 And the woman said to Elias: Now, in this I have known that thou art a man of God, and the word of our Lord in thy mouth is true.
\c 18
\p
\v 1 After many days the word of our Lord came to Elias, the third year, saying: Go, and shew thyself to Achab, that I may give rain upon the face of the earth.
\v 2 Elias therefore went to shew himself to Achab: and there was sore famine in Samaria.
\v 3 And Achab called Abdias the governor of his house: And Abdias did fear our Lord very much.
\v 4 For when Jezabel killed the Prophets of our Lord, he took an hundred Prophets, and hid them by fifty and fifty in caves, and fed them with bread and water.
\v 5 Achab therefore said to Abdias: Go into the land to all the fountains of waters, and into all valleys, if perhaps we may find grass, and save the horses and mules, and the beasts may not utterly perish.
\v 6 And they divided the countries between them, that they might go circuit about them: Achab went one way, and Abdias another way severally.
\v 7 And when Abdias was in the way, Elias met him: who when he knew him, fell on his face, and said: My lord, art not thou Elias? \f + \fr 18:7 \ft Abdias adored Elias as the Prophet of God, and a holy man, not with civil honour, for in the world Abdias was the greater person, nor with divine honour, for that had been idolatry. It was therefore religious honour, called dulia, due to spiritual excellency of God's servants.\f*
\v 8 To whom he answered: I am. Go, and tell thy lord: Elias is here.
\v 9 And he said: What have I sinned, that thou deliverest me thy servant into the hand of Achab, that he may kill me?
\v 10 Our Lord thy God liveth, there is no nation or Kingdom, whither my lord hath not sent to seek thee; and all answering: He is not here; he adjured all kingdoms and nations, for that thou wast not found.
\v 11 And now thou sayest to me: Go, and tell thy lord, Elias is here.
\v 12 And when I am departed from thee, the Spirit of our Lord will carry thee into a place, that I know not: and I entering in shall tell Achab, and not finding thee, he will kill me: and thy servant feareth our Lord from his infancy.
\v 13 Hath it not been told thee my lord, what I did when Jezabel killed the Prophets of our Lord, that I hid of the Prophets of our Lord an hundred men, by fifty and fifty in caves, and fed them with bread and water?
\v 14 And now thou sayst: Go, and tell thy lord: Elias is here: that he may kill me?
\v 15 And Elias said: The Lord of hosts liveth, before whose face I stand, this day will I appear to him.
\v 16 Abdias therefore went to meet Achab, and told him: and Achab came to meet Elias.
\v 17 And when he had seen him, he said: Art thou he that doest trouble Israel?
\v 18 And he said: not I have troubled Israel, but thou, and the house of thy father, who have forsaken the commandments of our Lord, & have followed Baalim.
\v 19 Nevertheless send now, and gather unto me all Israel in the mount of Carmel, and the Prophets of Baal four hundred fifty, and the Prophets of the groves four hundred, which eat of Jezabel's table.
\v 20 Achab sent to all the children of Israel, and gathered together the Prophets in the mount of Carmel.
\v 21 And Elias coming to all the people, said: How long halt you on two sides? If our Lord be God, follow him: but if Baal, follow him. And the people did not answer him a word. \f + \fr 18:21 \ft Such zealous expostulation is necessary to all Neutrals in religion who are neither hot nor cold, but lukewarm, such as Angels detest Apoc. 3.\f*
\v 22 And Elias said again to the people: I only remain a Prophet of our Lord: and the Prophets of Baal are four hundred and fifty men.
\v 23 Let two oxen be given us, and let them choose to themselves one oxe, and cutting it into pieces let them lay it upon wood, but put no fire under: and I will dress the other oxe, and will lay it upon wood, and put no fire under.
\v 24 Invocate ye the names of your gods, & I will invocate the name of my Lord: and the God that shall hear by fire, let the same be God. And all the people answering said, A very good proposition.
\v 25 Elias therefore said to the Prophets of Baal: Choose you one oxe, and make it first, because you are many: and invocate the names of your gods, and put no fire under.
\v 26 Who when they had taken the oxe, which he gave them, they dressed it: and they invocated the name of Baal from morning until midday, saying: Baal hear us. And there was no voice, nor any that answered: and they leaped over the altar, that they had made.
\v 27 And when it was now midday, Elias jested at them, saying: Cry with a louder voice: for he is God, and perhaps he speaketh, or is in his inn, or in the way, or at the least he sleepeth, that he must be waked.
\v 28 They cried therefore with a loud voice, and cut themselves after their rite with knives and lancets, till they were all imbrued with blood.
\v 29 And after the midday was past, and whilst they prophesied, the time was come, when they used to offer sacrifice, neither voice was heard, nor any did answer, nor attend them praying:
\v 30 Elias said to all the people: Come unto me. And the people coming to him, he repaired the altar of our Lord, that was destroyed.
\v 31 And he took twelve stones according to the number of the tribes of the children of Jacob, to whom the word of our Lord came, saying: Israel shall be thy name.
\v 32 And he built of the stones an altar in the name of our Lord: and he made a water gutter, as it were by two furrows round about the altar,
\v 33 And he laid the wood in order, and divided the oxe in joints, and laid it upon the wood,
\v 34 and said: Fill four buckets with water, and pour upon the holocaust, and upon the wood. And again he said: Do it also the second time. Who having done it the second time, he said: The third time also do the same. And they did so the third time,
\v 35 and the waters ran about the altar, and the trough of the conduit was filled.
\v 36 And when it was now time that the holocaust should be offered, Elias the Prophet coming said: Lord God of Abraham, and Isaac, and Israel, shew this day that thou art the God of Israel, and I thy servant, and that according to thy commandment I have done all these things.
\v 37 Hear me Lord, hear me that this people may learn, that thou art our Lord God, and thou hast converted their heart again. \f + \fr 18:37 \ft When miracles are attempted for trial of the truth, the devil's power is restrained, & only the truth is testified: Our Lord working withal, & confirming the doctrine with signs following. Marc. ult.\f*
\v 38 And the fire of our Lord fell, and devoured the holocaust, and the wood, and the stones, licking also the dust, and the water, that was in the water gutter.
\v 39 Which when all the people had seen, they fell on their face, and said: Our Lord he is God, our Lord he is God.
\v 40 And Elias said to them: Apprehend the Prophets of Baal, and let not one escape of them. Whom when they had taken, Elias brought them to the Torrent Cison, and killed them there.
\v 41 And Elias said to Achab: Go up, eat and drink: because there is sound of much rain.
\v 42 Achab went up to eat and drink: and Elias went up into the top of Carmel, and flat on the earth put his face between his knees,
\v 43 and he said to his servant: Go up, and look toward the sea. Who when he was gone up, and had looked, he said: There is nothing. And again he said to him: Return seven times.
\v 44 And in the seventh time: Behold a little cloud as it were a man's foot came up from the sea. Who said: Go up and say to Achab: Yoke thy chariot and go down, lest the rain prevent thee.
\v 45 And when he turned himself hither and thither, behold the heavens were darkened, and clouds, and wind, and there fell great rain. Achab therefore going up went into Jezrahel:
\v 46 and the hand of our Lord was made upon Elias, and his loins girded he ran before Achab, until he came into Jezrahel.
\c 19
\p
\v 0 thousand in Israel, which have not bowed to Baal.
\v 1 And Achab told Jezabel all things that Elias had done, and how he had killed all the prophets with the sword.
\v 2 And Jezabel sent a message to Elias, saying: These things do the gods to me, and these add they, if this hour tomorrow I make not thy soul as the soul of one of them.
\v 3 Elias therefore was afraid, and rising he went whither soever his will carried him: and he came into Bersabee of Juda, and left his servant there,
\v 4 and went forward into the desert, one day's journey. And when he was come, and sat under a juniper tree, he desired for his soul to die, and said: It sufficeth me Lord, take my soul: for I am not better than my fathers.
\v 5 And he cast himself down, & slept in the shadow of the juniper tree: & behold an Angel of our Lord touched him, and said to him: Arise, and eat.
\v 6 He looked, and behold at his head hearth-baked bread, and a vessel of water: he therefore did eat, & drink, & he slept again.
\v 7 And the Angel of our lord returned the second time, & touched him, & said to him: Arise, eat: for thou hast yet a great way to go.
\v 8 Who when he was risen, did eat & drink, and walked in the strength of that meat forty days, & forty nights, unto the mount of God, Horeb.
\v 9 And when he was come thither, he tarried in a cave, and behold the word of our Lord unto him, and he said to him: What doest thou here Elias?
\v 10 But he answered: With zeal have I been zealous for our Lord the God of hosts, because the children of Israel have forsaken thy covenant: thy altars have they destroyed, and thy Prophets they have slain with the sword, and I alone am left, and they seek my life to take it away. \f + \fr 19:10 \ft Elias knew no other at that instant in the ten tribes, that were not partakers in idolatry; but there were indeed seven thousand (v. 18.) that bowed not their knees to Baal. And the whole Kingdom of Juda observed true religion, where Asa then reigned, and after him Josaphat: both good Kings, chap. 15. v. 11. 22. v. 43. 2. Par. 15. &, 17.\f*
\v 11 And he said to him: Come forth, and stand in the mount before our Lord: and behold our Lord passeth, and a great wind and strong, overthrowing mountains and breaking rocks before our Lord: not in the wind is our Lord, and after the wind an earth quake: not in the earth quake is our Lord,
\v 12 and after the earth quake fire: not in the fire is our Lord, & after the fire a whistling of a gentle wind.
\v 13 Which when Elias had heard, he covered his face with his mantle, and coming forth stood in the door of the cave, and behold a voice unto him, saying: What doest thou here Elias?
\v 14 And he answered: With zeal have I been zealous for our Lord the God of hosts: because the children of Israel have forsaken thy covenant: thine altars they have destroyed, and thy Prophets they have slain with the sword, and I alone am left, and they seek my life to take it away.
\v 15 And our Lord said to him: Go, and return into thy way by the desert of Damascus: and when thou art come thither thou shalt anoint Hazael king over Syria, \f + \fr 19:15 \ft Elias prophesied that these two should be Kings, and cast his cloak over Elizeus. v. 19 Elizeus declared to Hazael that he should be King, 4. Reg. 8. another Prophet anointed Jehu, 4. Reg. 9.\f*
\v 16 and Jehu the son of Namsi thou shalt anoint king over Israel: and Eliseus the son of Saphat, which is of Abelmeula, thou shalt anoint prophet for thee.
\v 17 And it shall be, whosoever shall escape the sword of Hazael, him Jehu shall kill: and whosoever shall escape the sword of Jehu, him shall Eliseus kill.
\v 18 And I will leave me in Israel seven thousand men, whose knees have not been bowed before Baal, and every mouth, that hath not adored him kissing his hands.
\v 19 Elias therefore departing thence, found Eliseus the son of Saphat, ploughing with twelve yoke of oxen, and he was one of them that ploughed with twelve yoke of oxen: and when Elias came to him, he cast his mantle upon him.
\v 20 Who forthwith leaving the oxen ran after Elias, and said: Let me kiss, I pray thee, my father, and my mother, and so I will follow thee. And he said to him: Go, and return: for that which was my part, I have done to thee.
\v 21 And returning from him, he took a yoke of oxen, and killed them, and sod the flesh with the plough of the oxen, and gave to the people, and they did eat: and rising up he departed, and followed Elias, and ministered to him.
\c 20
\p
\v 1 Moreover Benadad the king of Syria, gathered together all his host, and two and thirty kings with him, & horses, & chariots: & going up fought against Samaria, and besieged it.
\v 2 And sending messengers to Achab the king of Israel into the city,
\v 3 he said: Thus saith Benadad: Thy silver, and thy gold is mine: and thy wives, and thy principal children be mine.
\v 4 And the king of Israel answered: According to thy word my lord king, I am thine, and all that is mine.
\v 5 And the messengers returning, said: Thus saith Benadad, which sent us unto thee: Thy silver, and thy gold, and thy wives, and thy children thou shalt give me.
\v 6 Tomorrow therefore this very hour I will send my servants to thee, and they shall search thy house, and the house of thy servants: and all that pleaseth them, they shall put in their hands, and take away.
\v 7 And the king of Israel called all the ancients of the land, and said: Mark, and see that he seeketh to entrap us. For he sent to me for my wives, and children, and for the silver and gold: and I said not nay.
\v 8 And all the ancients, and all the people said to him: Hear not, neither agree unto him.
\v 9 He therefore answered the messengers of Benadad: Tell my lord the king: All things for the which thou didst send to me thy servant in the beginning I will do: but this thing I cannot do.
\v 10 And the messengers returning made report unto him, who sent again, and said: These things do the gods to me, and these add they, if the dust of Samaria shall suffice for the handfuls of all the people, that followeth me.
\v 11 And the king of Israel answering, said: Tell him Let not the girded glory as the ungirded. \f + \fr 20:11 \ft Not at the putting on of armour, is time to boast of victory, but rather at putting it off. Those that are girded & strongly armed do unwisely in trusting their own strength, & contemning their adversaries: for by so doing they are often overthrown. And those that distrusting themselves trust in God, one way or other always prevail. A necessary lesson, both in temporal and spiritual warfare.\f*
\v 12 And it came to pass, when Benadad had heard this word, himself & the kings drank in pavilions, and he said to his servants: Beset the city, and they did beset it.
\v 13 And behold a Prophet coming to Achab the king of Israel, said to him: Thus saith our Lord, Hast thou indeed seen all this exceeding great multitude? Behold, I will deliver them into thy hand this day: that thou mayst know, that I am the Lord.
\v 14 And Achab said: By whom? And he said to him: Thus saith our Lord: By the servants of the princes of the provinces. And he said: Who shall begin to fight? And he said: Thou.
\v 15 He therefore mustered the servants of the Princes of the provinces, and he found the number of two hundred thirty two: and he mustered after them the people, all the children of Israel, seven thousand.
\v 16 And they went forth at noon. But Benadad drank all drunken in his tent. And two and thirty kings with him, which were come to aid him.
\v 17 The servants thereof of the Princes of the provinces issued forth in the forefront. Benadad therefore sent. Who told him, saying: Men are come forth out of Samaria.
\v 18 And he said: Whether they come for peace, take them alive: or else to fight, alive take ye them.
\v 19 The servants therefore of the Princes of the provinces issued forth, and the rest of the army followed:
\v 20 and every one struck the man that came against him: and the Syrians fled, and Israel pursued them. Benadad also the king of Syria fled on horseback with his horsemen.
\v 21 Moreover the king of Israel issuing forth struck the horses and chariots, & he struck Syria with a great slaughter.
\v 22 (And a Prophet coming to the king of Israel, said to him: Go, & take courage, & know, & see what thou doest: for the year following the king of Syria will come up against thee.)
\v 23 But the servants of the king of Syria said to him: The gods of the mountains be their gods, therefore have they overcome us: but it is better that we fight against them in the champion, and we shall overcome them.
\v 24 Thou therefore do this word: Remove all the kings from thine army, and put captains for them:
\v 25 and repair the number of soldiers, that are slain of thine, and horses according to the old horses, & chariots according to the chariots, which thou hadst before: and we will fight against them in the champion, and thou shalt see that we shall overcome them. He believed their counsel, and did so.
\v 26 Therefore after a year was passed, Benadad mustered the Syrians, and went up into Aphec, to fight against Israel.
\v 27 Moreover the children of Israel were mustered, and taking victuals they went forth on the contrary side, and camped against them, as it were two little flocks of goats: but the Syrians filled the land.
\v 28 (And a man of God coming, said to the king of Israel: Thus saith our Lord: Because the Syrians have said: The Lord is God of the mountains, and is not God of the Valleys, I will give all this great multitude into thy hand, and you shall know that I am the Lord.) \f + \fr 20:28 \ft Many victories and other benefits were bestowed upon Achab, to make him know God: but he contemning them all remained in his impiety, and finally was slain ch. 22. v. 38.\f*
\v 29 And seven days did these, and they direct their armies one against the other, and in the seventh day was the battle fought, and the children of Israel struck of the Syrians an hundred thousand footmen in one day.
\v 30 And they that remained in Aphec, fled into the city: and the wall fell upon seven and twenty thousand men, that were left. Moreover Benadad flying entered the city, into a chamber that was within a chamber,
\v 31 and his servants said to him: Behold, we have heard that the kings of the house of Israel are merciful: Let us therefore put sackcloths on our loins, and cords on our heads, and go forth to the king of Israel: perhaps he will save our lives.
\v 32 They girded their loins with sackcloths, and put cords on their heads, and came to the king of Israel, and said to him: Thy servant Benadad saith: Let my soul live, I beseech thee. And he said: If he be yet alive, he is my brother.
\v 33 Which the men took for good luck: and in haste caught the word of his mouth, and said: Thy brother Benadad. And he said to them: Go and bring him to me. Benadad therefore came out to him, and he lifted him up into his chariot.
\v 34 Who said to him: The cities which my father took from thy father, I will render: do thou make thee streets in Damascus, as my father made in Samaria, and I confederate will depart from thee. He therefore made a league, and dismissed him.
\v 35 Then a certain man of the children of the Prophets said to his fellow in the word of our Lord: Strike me. But he would not strike.
\v 36 To whom he said: Because thou wouldest not hear the word of our Lord, behold thou shalt depart from me, and a lion shall strike thee. And when he was departed a little from him, a lion found him, and slew him.
\v 37 But finding also another man, he said to him: Strike me. Who struck him, and wounded him.
\v 38 The Prophet therefore went, and met the king in the way, and with sprinkling of dust changed his face and his eyes.
\v 39 And when the king passed by, he cried to the king, and said: Thy servant went forth to fight hand strokes: and when a certain man was fled, one brought him to me, and said: Keep this man: who if he shall slip away, thy life shall be for his life, or thou shalt pay a talent of silver.
\v 40 And whilst I being troubled turned hither and thither, suddenly he appeared not. And the king of Israel said to him: This is thy judgment, which thyself hast decreed.
\v 41 But he forthwith wiped off the dust from his face, and the king of Israel knew him, that he was of the prophets.
\v 42 Who said to him: Thus saith our Lord: Because thou hast let go out of thy hand a man worthy to die, thy life shall be for his life, and thy people for his people. \f + \fr 20:42 \ft Foolish pity in sparing a dangerous and common enemy is offensive to God, & severely punished by his justice.\f*
\v 43 The king of Israel therefore returned into his house, contemning to hear, & raging came into Samaria.
\c 21
\p
\v 1 And after these words, at that time Naboth the Jezrahelite had a vineyard, which was in Jezrahel, beside the palace of Achab the king of Samaria.
\v 2 Achab therefore spake to Naboth, saying: Give me thy vineyard, that I may make me a garden of herbs, because it is nigh, and joining to my house, and I will give thee for it a better vineyard: or if thou think it more commodious for thee, the price of silver, so much as it is worth. \f + \fr 21:2 \ft If no subject were lord of any land, but only at the King's pleasure & Kings were proper lords of all the lands in their Kingdoms, then Achab might have taken Naboth's vineyard; especially giving him a better, or money for it. Neither was it a vain scruple in Naboth, to conserve his ancester's inheritance. For both his denial is here justified, and Achab's extortion condemned. S. Ambrose li. 2. offic. c. 9. counteth Naboth a Martyr, See Annot. 1. Reg. 8.\f*
\v 3 To whom Naboth answered: Our Lord be merciful to me, that I give not the inheritance of my fathers to thee.
\v 4 Achab therefore came into his house with indignation, and fretting upon the word that Naboth the Jezrahelite had spoken to him, saying: I will not give thee the inheritance of my fathers. And casting himself upon his bed, he turned away his face to the wall, and did not eat bread.
\v 5 And Jezabel his wife went in unto him, and said to him: What is this matter, whereupon thy soul is grieved? And why eatest thou not bread?
\v 6 Who answered her: I spake to Naboth the Jezrahelite, and said to him: Give me thy vineyard, taking money for it: or if it please thee, I will give thee a better vineyard for it. And he said: I will not give thee my vineyard.
\v 7 Jezabel therefore his wife said to him: Thou art of great authority, and doest well govern the Kingdom of Israel: Arise, and eat bread, and be of good cheer, I will give thee the vineyard of Naboth the Jezrahelite.
\v 8 She therefore wrote letters in the name of Achab, and signed them with his ring, and sent to the ancients, and the chief men that were in his city, and dwelt with Naboth.
\v 9 And this was the tenor of the letters: Proclaim a fast, and make Naboth sit among the chief of the people,
\v 10 and suborn two men the children of Belial against him, and let them bear false testimony: that he hath blessed God and the king: and bring him forth, and stone him, and so let him die. \f + \fr 21:10 \ft To avoid horror of blasphemy holy scripture often useth the term blessing for cursing.\f*
\v 11 His citizens therefore the ancients and chief men, that dwelt with him in the city, did as Jezabel had commanded them, and as it was written in the letters which she sent to them:
\v 12 they proclaimed a fast, and made Naboth sit among the chief of the people.
\v 13 And two men the children of the devil being brought forth, they made them sit against him: but they, as devilish men, gave testimony against him before the multitude: Naboth hath blessed God and the king: for the which thing they brought him forth without the city, and killed him with stones.
\v 14 And they sent to Jezabel, saying: Naboth is stoned, and is dead.
\v 15 And it came to pass, when Jezabel had heard that Naboth was stoned, and dead, she spake to Achab: Arise, and possess the vineyard of Naboth the Jezrahelite, who would not agree unto thee, and give it taking money: for Naboth liveth not, but is dead.
\v 16 Which when Achab had heard, to wit, that Naboth was dead, he arose, and went down into the vineyard of Naboth the Jezrahelite, to possess it.
\v 17 The word of our Lord therefore came to Elias the Thesbite, saying:
\v 18 Arise, and go down to meet Achab the king of Israel, who is in Samaria: behold he goeth down to the vineyard of Naboth, to possess it:
\v 19 and thou shalt speak to him, saying: Thus saith our Lord: Thou hast slain, moreover also thou hast possest. And after these words thou shalt add: Thus saith our Lord: In this place, wherein the dogs have licked the blood of Naboth, they shall lick thy blood also. \f + \fr 21:19 \ft * chap. 22. v. 38.\f*
\v 20 And Achab said to Elias: Hast thou found me thine enemy? Who said: I have found thee, for that thou art sold, to do evil in the sight of our Lord.
\v 21 Behold I will bring evil upon thee, and will cut down thy posterity, and will kill of Achab him that pisseth against the wall, and the inclosed, and the last in Israel.
\v 22 And I will make thy house, as the house of Jeroboam the son of Nabat, and as the house of Baasa the son of Ahias: because thou hast done to provoke me to anger, and hast made Israel to sin.
\v 23 But of Jezabel also our Lord spake, saying: The dogs shall eat Jezabel in the field of Jezrahel.
\v 24 If Achab die in the city, the dogs shall eat him: but if he die in the field, the fowls of the air shall eat him.
\v 25 Therefore there was not such another as Achab, who was sold to do evil in the sight of our Lord: for his wife Jezabel set him on, \f + \fr 21:25 \ft So addicted to wickedness, as if he had sold himself to the devil for some temporal profit, or pleasure: In your iniquities you are sold. Isaiæ 50. S. Aug. q. 102. c. utro. test. S. Greg. ho. 10. in Ezech.\f*
\v 26 and he became abominable, in so much that he followed the idols, which the Amorrheites had made, whom our Lord consumed before the face of the children of Israel.
\v 27 Therefore when Achab had heard these words, he rent his garments, and covered his flesh with haircloth, and fasted, and slept in sackcloth, and walked casting down his head.
\v 28 And the word of our lord came to Elias the Thesbite, saying:
\v 29 Hast thou not seen Achab humbled before me? Therefore, because he hath humbled himself for my sake, I will not bring in the evil in his days, but in his son's days will I bring the evil upon his house.
\c 22
\p
\v 1 There passed therefore three years without war between Syria and Israel.
\v 2 And in the third year, Josaphat the king of Juda went down to the king of Israel.
\v 3 (And the king of Israel said to his servants: are you ignorant that Ramoth Galaad is ours, and we neglect to take it out of the hand of the king of Syria?)
\v 4 And he said to Josaphat: Wilt thou come with me to fight into Ramoth Galaad?
\v 5 And Josaphat said to the king of Israel: As I am, so thou also: my people and thy people are one: and my horsemen thy horsemen. And Josaphat said to the king of Israel: Ask, I beseech thee, this day the word of our Lord.
\v 6 The king of Israel therefore assembled the prophets, about four hundred men, and he said to them: Shall I go into Ramoth Galaad to fight, or sit still? Who answered: Go up, and our Lord will give it into the king's hand.
\v 7 And Josaphat said: Is there not here some prophet of our Lord, that we may ask by him? \f + \fr 22:7 \ft The godly King Josaphat justly suspecting the schismatical false Prophets, advised the other King to consult a true Prophet of God.\f*
\v 8 And the king of Israel said to Josaphat: There is one man left, by whom we may ask our Lord: but I hate him, because he doeth not prophesy unto me good, but evil, Micheas the son of Jemla. To whom Josaphat said: Speak not so, o king.
\v 9 The king of Israel therefore called a certain eunuch, and said to him: Make haste, and bring hither Micheas the son of Jemla.
\v 10 And the king of Israel, and Josaphat the king of Juda sat each in his throne clothed with royal attire, in a court beside the door of the gate of Samaria, & all the Prophets prophesied before them.
\v 11 And Sedecias the son of Chanaana made himself horns of iron, and said: Thus saith our Lord: With these shalt thou strike Syria, till thou destroy it. \f + \fr 22:11 \ft False Prophets imitate true Prophets in some exterior things, to make their Prophecies seem more authentical. Such horns appeared in a prophetical vision to Zachary the Prophet. Zach. 1. v. 18.\f*
\v 12 And all the prophets in like manner prophesied, saying: Ascend into Ramoth Galaad, and go prosperously, & our Lord will deliver it into the king's hands.
\v 13 But the messenger, that went to call Micheas, spake to him, saying: Behold the words of the prophets with one mouth preach good things to the king: let thy word therefore be like to theirs, and speak good things.
\v 14 To whom Micheas said: Our Lord liveth, whatsoever our Lord shall tell me, that will I speak.
\v 15 He therefore came to the king, and the king said to him: Micheas, shall we go into Ramoth Galaad to fight, or sit still? To whom he answered: Ascend, and go prosperously, and our Lord will deliver it into the king's hands. \f + \fr 22:15 \ft The Prophet giveth not this for a resolute answer, but seeing the King will go, he prayeth he may go prosperously. And the King conceiveth no otherwise of his answer, and therefore urgeth him to answer resolutely in the next words: I adjure thee &c.\f*
\v 16 But the king said to him: I adjure thee again and again, that thou speak not to me but that which is true in the name of our Lord.
\v 17 And he said: I saw all Israel dispersed in the mountains, as sheep not having a shepherd, and our Lord said: These have no master, let every man return into his house in peace.
\v 18 (Therefore the king of Israel said to Josaphat: Did I not tell thee, that he doth not Prophesy me good, but always evil?)
\v 19 But he adding, said: Therefore hear the word of our Lord: I saw our Lord sitting upon his throne, and all the host of heaven assisting him on the right hand and on the left:
\v 20 and our Lord said: Who shall deceive Achab the king of Israel, that he may go up, and fall in Ramoth Galaad? And one saith these manner of words, and another otherwise.
\v 21 And there came forth a spirit, and stood before our Lord, and said: I will deceive him. To whom our Lord spake: Wherein?
\v 22 And he said: I will go forth, and be a lying spirit in the mouth of all his prophets. And our Lord said: Thou shalt deceive, and shalt prevail: go forth, and do so. \f + \fr 22:22 \ft The coherence of the text sheweth that God only permitted, but commanded not the devil to deceive Achab. So S. Augustin. li. 2. q. ult. ad Simpli. S. Greg. li. 2. c. 21. Moral. and other fathers explicate this and like places.\f*
\v 23 Now therefore behold our Lord hath given the spirit of lying in the mouth of all thy prophets, that are here, and our Lord hath spoken evil against thee.
\v 24 And Sedecias the son of Chanaana came, and smote Micheas on the cheek, and said: Hath the Spirit of our Lord left me, and hath it spoken to thee?
\v 25 And Micheas said: Thou shalt see in that day, when thou shalt enter into thy chamber, within the chamber to be hid. \f + \fr 22:25 \ft When this false Prophet heard that the King was slain he hid himself, fearing the King's sons, that they would kill him. Iosephus li. 8. c. 14. Antiq.\f*
\v 26 And the king of Israel said: Take Micheas, & let him tarry with Amon the governor of the city, and with Joas the son of Amelech,
\v 27 and tell them: Thus saith the king: Cast this man into prison, and feed him with bread of tribulation, and water of distress, till I return in peace.
\v 28 And Micheas said: If thou return in peace, our Lord hath not spoken in me. And he said: Hear all ye peoples.
\v 29 Therefore the king of Israel went up, and Josaphat the king of Juda into Ramoth Galaad.
\v 30 The king of Israel therefore said to Josaphat: Take armour, and go into the battle, and put on thine own garments. Moreover the king of Israel changed his habit, and went into the battle.
\v 31 And the king of Syria had commanded the princes of his chariots thirty and two, saying: You shall not fight against any lesser, or greater, but against the king of Israel only.
\v 32 When therefore the Princes of the chariots had seen Josaphat, they suspected that he was the king of Israel, & making a violent assault they fought against him: and Josaphat cried out.
\v 33 And the Princes of the chariots perceived that he was not the king of Israel, and they ceased from him.
\v 34 And a certain man bent his bow; directing the arrow at all adventure, and by chance he struck the king of Israel between the lungs and the stomach. But he said to his coacher: Turn thy hand, and carry me out of the army, because I am grievously wounded. \f + \fr 22:34 \ft It happened by chance in respect of the archer's intention, but otherwise by God's providence directing his hand. So Achab's crafty persuading Josaphat to put on his kingly attire (v. 30.) himself fighting in vulgar armour, saved him not from just revenge.\f*
\v 35 The battle therefore was fought that day, and the king of Israel stood in his chariot against the Syrians, and he died in the evening: and the blood of the wound ran into the midst of the chariot,
\v 36 and the herald sounded in all the army before the sun set, saying: Every man return into his city, and into his country.
\v 37 And the king died, and was carried into Samaria: and they buried the king in Samaria,
\v 38 & washed his chariot in the pool of Samaria, and the dogs licked his blood, and they washed the reins of the bridle, according to the word of our Lord which he had spoken.
\v 39 But the rest of the words of Achab, and all that he did, and the house of ivory that he built, and of all the cities that he built, are not these things written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Israel?
\v 40 Achab therefore slept with his fathers, and Ochozias his son reigned for him.
\v 41 But Josaphat the son of Asa began to reign over Juda the fourth year of Achab the king of Israel.
\v 42 Five and thirty years old was he when he began to reign, and five and twenty years he reigned in Jerusalem: the name of his mother was Azuba the daughter of Salai.
\v 43 And he walked in all the way of Asa his father, and he declined not from it: and he did that which was right in the sight of our Lord.
\v 44 But yet he took not away the excelses: for as yet the people did sacrifice, and burnt incense in the excelses.
\v 45 And Josaphat had peace with the king of Israel.
\v 46 But the rest of the words of Josaphat, and his works, which he did, and his battles, are not these things written in the Book of the words of the days of the kings of Juda?
\v 47 Yea and the remnant of the effeminate, which remained in the days of Asa his father, he took out of the land.
\v 48 Neither was there then a king appointed in Edom.
\v 49 But king Josaphat had made navies on the sea, which should sail into Ophir for gold: and they could not go, because they were broken in Asiongaber.
\v 50 Then said Ochozias the son of Achab to Josaphat: Let my servants go with thy servants in the ships. And Josaphat would not.
\v 51 And Josaphat slept with his fathers, and was buried with them in the City of David his father: and Joram his son reigned for him.
\v 52 And Ochozias the son of Achab began to reign over Israel in Samaria, in the seventeenth year of Josaphat the king of Juda, and he reigned over Israel two years.
\v 53 And he did evil in the sight of our Lord, and walked in the way of his father and his mother, and in the way of Jeroboam the son of Nabat, who made Israel to sin.
\v 54 He served also Baal, and adored him, and provoked our Lord the God of Israel, according to all things which his father had done.
